# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: air-fuel-ratio
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] In the study of combustion, the **adiabatic flame temperature** is the temperature reached by a flame under ideal conditions.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] It is an upper bound of the temperature that is reached in actual processes.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] There are two types of adiabatic flame temperature: *constant volume* and *constant pressure*, depending on how the process is completed.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] The constant volume adiabatic flame temperature is the temperature that results from a complete combustion process that occurs without any work, heat transfer or changes in kinetic or potential energy.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] Its temperature is higher than in the *constant pressure* process because no energy is utilized to change the volume of the system (i.e., generate work).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] In daily life, the vast majority of flames one encounters are those caused by rapid oxidation of hydrocarbons in materials such as wood, wax, fat, plastics, propane, and gasoline.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] The constant-pressure adiabatic flame temperature of such substances in air is in a relatively narrow range around 1,950 °C (2,220 K; 3,540 °F).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] This is mostly because the heat of combustion of these compounds is roughly proportional to the amount of oxygen consumed, which proportionally increases the amount of air that has to be heated, so the effect of a larger heat of combustion on the flame temperature is offset.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] Incomplete reaction at higher temperature further curtails the effect of a larger heat of combustion.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] Because most combustion processes that happen naturally occur in the open air, there is nothing that confines the gas to a particular volume like the cylinder in an engine.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] As a result, these substances will burn at a constant pressure, which allows the gas to expand during the process.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] Assuming initial atmospheric conditions (1 bar and 20 °C), the following table lists the flame temperature for various fuels under constant pressure conditions.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] The temperatures mentioned here are for a stoichiometric fuel-oxidizer mixture (i.e. equivalence ratio *φ* = 1).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] These are theoretical, not actual, flame temperatures produced by a flame that loses no heat.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] The closest will be the hottest part of a flame, where the combustion reaction is most efficient.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] This also assumes complete combustion (e.g. perfectly balanced, non-smoky, usually bluish flame).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] Several values in the table significantly disagree with the literature or predictions by online calculators.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] where, ${}_{R}Q_{P}$ and ${}_{R}W_{P}$ are the heat and work transferred from the system to the surroundings during the process, respectively, and $U_{R}$ and $U_{P}$ are the internal energy of the reactants and products, respectively.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] There is also no heat transfer because the process is defined to be adiabatic: ${}_{R}Q_{P}=0$ .
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] As a result, the internal energy of the products is equal to the internal energy of the reactants: $U_{P}=U_{R}$ .
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] Again there is no heat transfer occurring because the process is defined to be adiabatic: ${}_{R}Q_{P}=0$ .
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] Recalling the definition of enthalpy we obtain $H_{P}=H_{R}$ .
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] We see that the adiabatic flame temperature of the constant pressure process is lower than that of the constant volume process.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] This is because some of the energy released during combustion goes, as work, into changing the volume of the control system.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] If we make the assumption that combustion goes to completion (i.e. forming only CO 2 and H 2O), we can calculate the adiabatic flame temperature by hand either at stoichiometric conditions or lean of stoichiometry (excess air).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] and use the equilibrium constant for this reaction, we will have enough variables to complete the calculation.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] Different fuels with different levels of energy and molar constituents will have different adiabatic flame temperatures.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] We can see by the following figure why nitromethane (CH3NO2) is often used as a power boost for cars.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] Since each molecule of nitromethane contains an oxidant with relatively high-energy bonds between nitrogen and oxygen, it can burn much hotter than hydrocarbons or oxygen-containing methanol.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] This is analogous to adding pure oxygen, which also raises the adiabatic flame temperature.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] This in turn allows it to build up more pressure during a constant volume process.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] The higher the pressure, the more force upon the piston creating more work and more power in the engine.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] It stays relatively hot rich of stoichiometry because it contains its own oxidant.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] However, continual running of an engine on nitromethane will eventually melt the piston and/or cylinder because of this higher temperature.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] In real world applications, complete combustion does not typically occur.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] Chemistry dictates that dissociation and kinetics will change the composition of the products.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] There are a number of programs available that can calculate the adiabatic flame temperature taking into account dissociation through equilibrium constants (Stanjan, NASA CEA, AFTP).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] The following figure illustrates that the effects of dissociation tend to lower the adiabatic flame temperature.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/adiabatic-flame-temperature] This result can be explained through Le Chatelier's principle.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] In an internal combustion engine or industrial furnace, the air–fuel ratio is an important measure for anti-pollution and performance-tuning reasons.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] If exactly enough air is provided to completely burn all of the fuel (**stoichiometric combustion**), the ratio is known as the **stoichiometric mixture**, often abbreviated to **stoich**.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Ratios lower than stoichiometric (where the fuel is in excess) are considered "rich".
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Rich mixtures are less efficient, but may produce more power and burn cooler.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Ratios higher than stoichiometric (where the air is in excess) are considered "lean".
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Lean mixtures are more efficient but may cause higher temperatures, which can lead to the formation of nitrogen oxides.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Some engines are designed with features to allow lean-burn.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] For precise air–fuel ratio calculations, the oxygen content of combustion air should be specified because of different air density due to different altitude or intake air temperature, possible dilution by ambient water vapor, or enrichment by oxygen additions.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] An **air-fuel ratio meter** monitors the air–fuel ratio of an internal combustion engine.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Also called **air–fuel ratio gauge**, **air–fuel meter**, or **air–fuel gauge**, it reads the voltage output of an oxygen sensor, sometimes also called **AFR sensor** or lambda sensor.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] The original narrow-band oxygen sensors became factory installed standard in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] In recent years a newer and much more accurate wide-band sensor, though more expensive, has become available.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Most stand-alone narrow-band meters have 10 LEDs and some have more.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Also common, narrow band meters in round housings with the standard mounting 52 and 67 mm (2+1⁄16 and 2+5⁄8 in) diameters, as other types of car 'gauges'.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Analogue 'needle' style gauges are also available.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] In theory, a stoichiometric mixture has just enough air to completely burn the available fuel.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] In practice, this is never quite achieved, due primarily to the very short time available in an internal combustion engine for each combustion cycle.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Most of the combustion process is completed in approximately 2 milliseconds at an engine speed of 6,000 revolutions per minute (100 revolutions per second, or 10 milliseconds per revolution of the crankshaft.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] For a four-stroke engine this would mean 5 milliseconds for each piston stroke, and 20 milliseconds to complete one 720 degree Otto cycle).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] This is the time that elapses from the spark plug firing until 90% of the fuel–air mix is combusted, typically some 80 degrees of crankshaft rotation later.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Catalytic converters are designed to work best when the exhaust gases passing through them are the result of nearly perfect combustion.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] A perfectly stoichiometric mixture burns very hot and can damage engine components if the engine is placed under high load at this fuel–air mixture.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Due to the high flame temperatures at this mixture, detonation is possible under high load.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] (Detonation is known as knocking or pinging).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Such detonation can cause serious engine damage as the uncontrolled burning of the fuel-air mix can create very high pressures in the cylinder.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] As a consequence, stoichiometric mixtures are only used under light to low-moderate load conditions.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] For acceleration and high-load conditions, a richer mixture (lower air–fuel ratio) is used to produce cooler combustion products and so avoid overheating of the cylinder head, and thus prevent detonation.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] The stoichiometric mixture for a gasoline engine is the ideal ratio of air to fuel that burns all fuel with no excess air.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] For gasoline fuel, the stoichiometric air–fuel mixture is about 14.7:1 i.e. for every one gram of fuel, 14.7 grams of air are required.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Any mixture greater than 14.7:1 is considered a lean mixture; any less than 14.7:1 is a rich mixture – given perfect (ideal) "test" fuel (gasoline consisting of solely *n*-heptane and iso-octane).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] In reality, most fuels consist of a combination of heptane, octane, a handful of other alkanes, plus additives including detergents, and possibly oxygenators such as MTBE (methyl *tert*-butyl ether) or ethanol/methanol.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] These compounds all alter the stoichiometric ratio, with most of the additives pushing the ratio downward (oxygenators bring extra oxygen to the combustion event in liquid form that is released at the time of combustions; for MTBE-laden fuel, a stoichiometric ratio can be as low as 14.1:1).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Vehicles that use an oxygen sensor or other feedback loops to control fuel to air ratio (lambda control), compensate automatically for this change in the fuel's stoichiometric rate by measuring the exhaust gas composition and controlling fuel volume.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Vehicles that use oxygen sensors can monitor the air–fuel ratio with an air–fuel ratio meter.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] In the typical air to natural gas combustion burner, a double-cross limit strategy is employed to ensure ratio control.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] The strategy involves adding the opposite flow feedback into the limiting control of the respective gas (air or fuel).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] This assures ratio control within an acceptable margin.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] There are other terms commonly used when discussing the mixture of air and fuel in internal combustion engines.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Air-fuel ratio is the ratio between the *mass* of air and the mass of fuel in the air-fuel mix at any given moment.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] The mass is the mass of all constituents that compose the air or fuel, whether they take part in the combustion or not.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] For pure octane the stoichiometric mixture is approximately 15.1:1, or *λ* of 1.00 exactly.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] In naturally aspirated engines powered by octane, maximum power is frequently reached at AFRs ranging from 12.5 to 13.3:1 or *λ* of 0.850 to 0.901.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] The air-fuel ratio of 12:1 is considered as the maximum output ratio, whereas the air-fuel ratio of 16:1 is considered as the maximum fuel economy ratio.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Air–fuel equivalence ratio, *λ* (lambda), is the ratio of actual AFR to stoichiometry for a given mixture.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] *λ* = 1.0 is at stoichiometry, rich mixtures *λ* < 1.0, and lean mixtures *λ* > 1.0.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] There is a direct relationship between *λ* and AFR.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] To calculate AFR from a given *λ*, multiply the measured *λ* by the stoichiometric AFR for that fuel.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Alternatively, to recover *λ* from an AFR, divide AFR by the stoichiometric AFR for that fuel.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Because the composition of common fuels varies seasonally, and because many modern vehicles can handle different fuels when tuning, it makes more sense to talk about *λ* values rather than AFR.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Most practical AFR devices actually measure the amount of residual oxygen (for lean mixes) or unburnt hydrocarbons (for rich mixtures) in the exhaust gas.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] The **fuel–air equivalence ratio**, *Φ* (phi), of a system is defined as the ratio of the fuel-to-oxidizer ratio to the stoichiometric fuel-to-oxidizer ratio.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] where *m* represents the mass, *n* represents a number of moles, subscript st stands for stoichiometric conditions.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] The advantage of using equivalence ratio over fuel–oxidizer ratio is that it takes into account (and is therefore independent of) both mass and molar values for the fuel and the oxidizer.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] Consider, for example, a mixture of one mole of ethane (C 2H 6) and one mole of oxygen (O 2).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] To compare it with the equivalence ratio, we need to determine the fuel–oxidizer ratio of ethane and oxygen mixture.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] This is not the case if one uses fuel–oxidizer ratio, which takes different values for different mixtures.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] In industrial fired heaters, power plant steam generators, and large gas-fired turbines, the more common terms are percent excess combustion air and percent stoichiometric air.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] For example, excess combustion air of 15 percent means that 15 percent more than the required stoichiometric air (or 115 percent of stoichiometric air) is being used.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] A combustion control point can be defined by specifying the percent excess air (or oxygen) in the oxidant, or by specifying the percent oxygen in the combustion product.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air-fuel-ratio-meter] An air–fuel ratio meter may be used to measure the percent oxygen in the combustion gas, from which the percent excess oxygen can be calculated from stoichiometry and a mass balance for fuel combustion.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The **atmosphere of Earth** consists of a layer of mixed gas (commonly referred to as **air**) that is retained by gravity, surrounding the Earth's surface.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] It contains variable quantities of suspended aerosols and particulates that create weather features such as clouds and hazes.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The atmosphere serves as a protective buffer between the Earth's surface and outer space.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] It shields the surface from most meteoroids and ultraviolet solar radiation, reduces diurnal temperature variation – the temperature extremes between day and night, and keeps it warm through heat retention via the greenhouse effect.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The atmosphere redistributes heat and moisture among different regions via air currents, and provides the chemical and climate conditions that allow life to exist and evolve on Earth.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] By mole fraction (i.e., by quantity of molecules), dry air contains 78.08% nitrogen, 20.95% oxygen, 0.93% argon, 0.04% carbon dioxide, and small amounts of other trace gases (see Composition below for more detail).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Air also contains a variable amount of water vapor, on average around 1% at sea level, and 0.4% over the entire atmosphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Earth's primordial atmosphere consisted of gases accreted from the solar nebula, but the composition changed significantly over time, affected by many factors such as volcanism, outgassing, impact events, weathering and the evolution of life (particularly the photoautotrophs).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] In the present day, human activity has contributed to atmospheric changes, such as climate change (mainly through deforestation and fossil-fuel–related global warming), ozone depletion and acid deposition.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The atmosphere has a mass of about 5.15×1018 kg, three quarters of which is within about 11 km (6.8 mi; 36,000 ft) of the surface.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The atmosphere becomes thinner with increasing altitude, with no definite boundary between the atmosphere and outer space.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The Kármán line at 100 km (62 mi) is often used as a conventional definition of the edge of space.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Several layers can be distinguished in the atmosphere based on characteristics such as temperature and composition, namely the troposphere, stratosphere, mesosphere, thermosphere (formally the ionosphere), and exosphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Air composition, temperature and atmospheric pressure vary with altitude.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Air suitable for use in photosynthesis by terrestrial plants and respiration of terrestrial animals is found within the troposphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The study of Earth's atmosphere and its processes is called atmospheric science (aerology), and includes multiple subfields, such as climatology and atmospheric physics.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Early pioneers in the field include Léon Teisserenc de Bort and Richard Assmann.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The study of the historic atmosphere is called paleoclimatology.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The three major constituents of Earth's atmosphere are nitrogen, oxygen, and argon.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Water vapor accounts for roughly 0.25% of the atmosphere by mass.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The remaining gases are often referred to as trace gases, among which are other greenhouse gases, principally carbon dioxide, methane, nitrous oxide, and ozone.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Besides argon, other noble gases, neon, helium, krypton, and xenon are also present.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Filtered air includes trace amounts of many other chemical compounds.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Many substances of natural origin may be present in locally and seasonally variable small amounts as aerosols in an unfiltered air sample, including dust of mineral and organic composition, pollen and spores, sea spray, and volcanic ash.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Various industrial pollutants also may be present as gases or aerosols, such as chlorine (elemental or in compounds), fluorine compounds, and elemental mercury vapor.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Sulfur compounds such as hydrogen sulfide and sulfur dioxide (SO2) may be derived from natural sources or from industrial air pollution.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The average molecular weight of dry air, which can be used to calculate densities or to convert between mole fraction and mass fraction, is about 28.946 or 28.964 g/mol.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] This is decreased when the air is humid.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Up to an altitude of around 100 km (62 mi), atmospheric turbulence mixes the component gases so that their relative concentrations remain the same.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] There exists a transition zone from roughly 80 to 120 km (50 to 75 mi) where this turbulent mixing gradually yields to molecular diffusion.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The latter process forms the heterosphere where the relative concentration of lighter gases increase with altitude.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] In general, air pressure and density decrease with altitude in the atmosphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] However, temperature has a more complicated profile with altitude and may remain relatively constant or even increase with altitude in some regions (see the temperature section).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Because the general pattern of the temperature/altitude profile, or lapse rate, is constant and measurable by means of instrumented balloon soundings, the temperature behavior provides a useful metric to distinguish atmospheric layers.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The exosphere is the outermost layer of Earth's atmosphere (though it is so tenuous that some scientists consider it to be part of interplanetary space rather than part of the atmosphere).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] It extends from the thermopause (also known as the "exobase") at the top of the thermosphere to a poorly defined boundary with the solar wind and interplanetary medium.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The altitude of the exobase varies from about 500 kilometres (310 mi; 1,600,000 ft) to about 1,000 kilometres (620 mi) in times of higher incoming solar radiation.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The upper limit varies depending on the definition.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Various authorities consider it to end at about 10,000 kilometres (6,200 mi) or about 190,000 kilometres (120,000 mi)—about halfway to the moon, where the influence of Earth's gravity is about the same as radiation pressure from sunlight.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The geocorona visible in the far ultraviolet (caused by neutral hydrogen) extends to at least 100,000 kilometres (62,000 mi).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] This layer is mainly composed of extremely low densities of hydrogen, with limited amounts of helium, carbon dioxide, and nascent oxygen closer to the exobase.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The atoms and molecules are so far apart that they can travel hundreds of kilometres without colliding with one another.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Thus, the exosphere no longer behaves like a gas, and the particles constantly escape into space.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] These free-moving particles follow ballistic trajectories and may migrate in and out of the magnetosphere or the solar wind.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Every second, the Earth loses about 3 kg of hydrogen, 50 g of helium, and much smaller amounts of other constituents.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The exosphere is too far above Earth for meteorological phenomena to be possible.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The exosphere contains many of the artificial satellites that orbit Earth.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The thermosphere is the second-highest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] It extends from the mesopause (which separates it from the mesosphere) at an altitude of about 80 km (50 mi) up to the thermopause at an altitude range of 500–1000 km (310–620 mi).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The height of the thermopause varies considerably due to changes in solar activity.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The passage of the dusk and dawn solar terminator creates background density perturbations up to a factor of two through this layer, forming a dominant feature in this region.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Because the thermopause lies at the lower boundary of the exosphere, it is also referred to as the exobase.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Overlapping the thermosphere, from 50 to 600 kilometres (31 to 373 mi) above Earth's surface, is the ionosphere – a region of enhanced plasma density.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The temperature of the thermosphere gradually increases with height and can rise as high as 1500 °C (2700 °F), though the gas molecules are so far apart that its temperature in the usual sense is not very meaningful.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] This temperature increase is caused by absorption of ionizing UV and X-ray emission from the Sun.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The air is so rarefied that an individual molecule (of oxygen, for example) travels an average of 1 kilometre (0.62 mi; 3300 ft) between collisions with other molecules.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Although the thermosphere has a high proportion of molecules with high energy, it would not feel hot to a human in direct contact, because its density is too low to conduct a significant amount of energy to or from the skin.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] This layer is completely cloudless and free of water vapor.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] However, non-hydrometeorological phenomena such as the aurora borealis and aurora australis are occasionally seen in the thermosphere at an altitude of around 100 km (62 mi).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The colors of the aurora are linked to the properties of the atmosphere at the altitude they occur.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The most common is the green aurora, which comes from atomic oxygen in the 1S state, and occurs at altitudes from 120 to 400 km (75 to 250 mi).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The International Space Station orbits in the thermosphere, between 370 and 460 km (230 and 290 mi).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] It is this layer where many of the satellites orbiting the Earth are present.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The mesosphere is the third highest layer of Earth's atmosphere, occupying the region above the stratosphere and below the thermosphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] It extends from the stratopause at an altitude of about 50 km (31 mi) to the mesopause at 80–85 km (50–53 mi) above sea level.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Temperatures drop with increasing altitude to the mesopause that marks the top of this middle layer of the atmosphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] It is the coldest place on Earth and has an average temperature around −85 °C (−120 °F; 190 K).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Because the atmosphere absorbs sound waves at a rate that is proportional to the square of the frequency, audible sounds from the ground do not reach the mesosphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Infrasonic waves can reach this altitude, but they are difficult to emit at a high power level.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Just below the mesopause, the air is so cold that even the very scarce water vapor at this altitude can condense into polar-mesospheric noctilucent clouds of ice particles.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] These are the highest clouds in the atmosphere and may be visible to the naked eye if sunlight reflects off them about an hour or two after sunset or similarly before sunrise.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] They are most readily visible when the Sun is around 4 to 16 degrees below the horizon.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Lightning-induced discharges known as transient luminous events (TLEs) occasionally form in the mesosphere above tropospheric thunderclouds.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The mesosphere is also the layer where most meteors and satellites burn up upon atmospheric entrance.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] It is too high above Earth to be accessible to jet-powered aircraft and balloons, and too low to permit orbital spacecraft.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The mesosphere is mainly accessed by sounding rockets and rocket-powered aircraft.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The stratosphere is the second-lowest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] It lies above the troposphere and is separated from it by the tropopause.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] This layer extends from the top of the troposphere at roughly 12 km (7.5 mi) above Earth's surface to the stratopause at an altitude of about 50 to 55 km (31 to 34 mi).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] 99% of the total mass of the atmosphere lies below 30 km (19 mi), and the atmospheric pressure at the top of the stratosphere is roughly 1/1000 the pressure at sea level.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] It contains the ozone layer, which is the part of Earth's atmosphere that contains relatively high concentrations of that gas.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The stratosphere defines a layer in which temperatures rise with increasing altitude.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] This rise in temperature is caused by the absorption of ultraviolet radiation (UV) from the Sun by the ozone layer, which restricts turbulence and mixing.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Although the temperature may be −80 °C (−110 °F; 190 K) at the tropopause, the top of the stratosphere is much warmer, and may be just below 0 °C.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] This layer is unique to the Earth; neither Mars nor Venus have a stratosphere because of low abundances of oxygen in their atmospheres.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The stratospheric temperature profile creates very stable atmospheric conditions, so the stratosphere lacks the weather-producing air turbulence that is so prevalent in the troposphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Consequently, the stratosphere is almost completely free of clouds and other forms of weather.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] However, polar stratospheric or nacreous clouds are occasionally seen in the lower part of this layer of the atmosphere where the air is coldest.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The stratosphere is the highest layer that can be accessed by jet-powered aircraft.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The troposphere is the lowest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] It extends from Earth's surface to an average height of about 12 km (7.5 mi), although this altitude varies from about 9 km (5.6 mi) at the geographic poles to 17 km (11 mi) at the Equator, with some variation due to weather.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The troposphere is bounded above by the tropopause, a boundary marked in most places by a temperature inversion (i.e. a layer of relatively warm air above a colder one), and in others by a zone that is isothermal with height.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Although variations do occur, the temperature usually declines with increasing altitude in the troposphere because the troposphere is mostly heated through energy transfer from the surface.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Thus, the lowest part of the troposphere (i.e.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Earth's surface) is typically the warmest section of the troposphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] This promotes vertical mixing (hence, the origin of its name in the Greek word τρόπος, *tropos*, meaning "turn").
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The troposphere contains roughly 80% of the mass of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The troposphere is denser than all its overlying layers because a larger atmospheric weight sits on top of the troposphere and causes it to be more severely compressed.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Fifty percent of the total mass of the atmosphere is located in the lower 5.5 km (3.4 mi) of the troposphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Nearly all atmospheric water vapor or moisture is found in the troposphere, so it is the layer where most of Earth's weather takes place.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The ability of the atmosphere to retain water decreases as the temperature declines, so 90% of the water vapor is held in the lower part of the troposphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] It has basically all the weather-associated cloud genus types generated by active wind circulation, although very tall cumulonimbus thunder clouds can penetrate the tropopause from below and rise into the lower part of the stratosphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Most conventional aviation activity takes place in the troposphere, and it is the only layer accessible by propeller-driven aircraft.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Contrails are formed from jet engine water emission at altitudes where the atmospheric temperature is about −53 °C (−63 °F); typically around 7.7 km (4.8 mi) for modern engines.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Above this altitude lies the heterosphere, which includes the exosphere and most of the thermosphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Here, the chemical composition varies with altitude.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] is large compared with the size of motions that cause mixing.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] with the heavier ones, such as oxygen and nitrogen, present only near the bottom of the heterosphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The upper part of the heterosphere is composed almost completely of hydrogen, the lightest element.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The average temperature of the atmosphere at Earth's surface is 14 °C (57 °F; 287 K) or 15 °C (59 °F; 288 K), depending on the reference.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The average atmospheric pressure at sea level is defined by the International Standard Atmosphere as 101325 pascals (760.00 Torr; 14.6959 psi; 760.00 mmHg).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] This is sometimes referred to as a unit of standard atmospheres (atm).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Total atmospheric mass is 5.1480×1018 kg (1.13494×1019 lb), about 2.5% less than would be inferred from the average sea-level pressure and Earth's area of 51007.2 megahectares, this portion being displaced by Earth's mountainous terrain.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Atmospheric pressure is the total weight of the air above unit area at the point where the pressure is measured.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Thus air pressure varies with location and weather.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Air pressure decreases exponentially with altitude at a rate that depends on the air temperature.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The rate of decrease is determined by a temperature-dependent parameter called the scale height: for each increase in altitude by this height, the pressure decreases by a factor of *e* (the base of natural logarithms, approximately 2.718).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] For Earth, this value is typically 5.5 to 6 km for altitudes up to around 80 km (50 mi).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] However, the atmosphere is more accurately modeled with a customized equation for each layer that takes gradients of temperature, molecular composition, solar radiation and gravity into account.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] At heights over 100 km, the atmosphere is not well mixed, so each chemical species has its own scale height.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] At altitudes of 200 to 300 km, the combined scale height is 20 to 30 km.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Even above the Kármán line, significant atmospheric effects such as auroras still occur.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Meteors begin to glow in this region, though the larger ones may not burn up until they penetrate more deeply.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The various layers of Earth's ionosphere, important to HF radio propagation, begin below 100 km and extend beyond 500 km.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] By comparison, the International Space Station typically orbit at 370–460 km, within the F-layer of the ionosphere, where they encounter enough atmospheric drag to require reboosts every few months, otherwise orbital decay will occur, resulting in a return to Earth.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Depending on solar activity, satellites can experience noticeable atmospheric drag at altitudes as high as 600–800 km.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Starting at sea level, the temperature decreases with altitude until reaching the stratosphere at around 11 km.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Above, the temperature stabilizes over a large vertical distance.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Starting above about 20 km, the temperature increases with height, due to heating within the ozone layer caused by the capture of significant ultraviolet radiation from the Sun by the molecular oxygen and ozone gas in this region.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] A second region of increasing temperature with altitude occurs at very high altitudes, in the aptly-named thermosphere above 90 km.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] During the night, the ground radiates more energy than it gains from the atmosphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] As energy is conducted from the nearby atmosphere to the cooler ground, it creates a temperature inversion where the local temperature increases with altitude up to around 1,000 m.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] For example, at sea level the speed of sound is 340 m/s.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] At the average temperature of the stratosphere, −60 °C, the speed of sound decreases to 290 m/s.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Density is not measured directly but is calculated from measurements of temperature, pressure and humidity using the equation of state for air (a form of the ideal gas law).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Atmospheric density decreases as the altitude increases.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] This variation can be approximately modeled using the barometric formula.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] More sophisticated models are used to predict the orbital decay of satellites.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The average mass of the atmosphere is about 5 quadrillion (5×1015) tonnes or 1/1,200,000 the mass of Earth.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] According to the American National Center for Atmospheric Research, "The total mean mass of the atmosphere is 5.1480×1018 kg with an annual range due to water vapor of 1.2 or 1.5×1015 kg, depending on whether surface pressure or water vapor data are used; somewhat smaller than the previous estimate.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Solar radiation (or sunlight) is the energy Earth receives from the Sun.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Earth also emits radiation back into space, but at longer wavelengths that humans cannot see.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] As energy propagates through the atmosphere, it is impacted by the process of radiative transfer.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] That is, some of the incoming and emitted radiation is subject to absorption, emission, and scattering by the atmosphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Another portion of the incident energy is reflected, with the two most important atmospheric reflectors being dust and clouds.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Depending on the properties of the aerosol, clouds can reflect up to 70% of the incident radiation.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Globally, clouds reflect 20% of the incoming energy, contributing two thirds of the planet's total albedo.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] In May 2017, glints of light, seen as twinkling from an orbiting satellite a million miles away, were found to be reflected light from ice crystals in the troposphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] When light passes through Earth's atmosphere, photons interact with it through *scattering*.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] If the light does not interact with the atmosphere, it is called *direct radiation* and is what you see if you were to look directly at the Sun.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] *Indirect radiation* is light that has been scattered in the atmosphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] For example, on an overcast day when you cannot see your shadow, there is no direct radiation reaching you, it has all been scattered.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] As another example, due to a phenomenon called Rayleigh scattering, shorter (blue) wavelengths scatter more easily than longer (red) wavelengths.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] This is why the sky looks blue; you are seeing scattered blue light.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Because the Sun is close to the horizon, the Sun's rays pass through more atmosphere than normal before reaching your eye.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Much of the blue light has been scattered out, leaving the red light in a sunset.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Different molecules absorb different wavelengths of radiation.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] For example, O2 and O3 absorb almost all radiation with wavelengths shorter than 300 nanometres.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Water (H2O) absorbs at many wavelengths above 700 nm.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] When a molecule absorbs a photon, it increases the energy of the molecule.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] This heats the atmosphere, but the atmosphere also cools by emitting radiation, as discussed below.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] In astronomical spectroscopy, the absorption of specific frequencies by the atmosphere is referred to as telluric contamination.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The combined absorption spectra of the gases in the atmosphere leave "windows" of low opacity, allowing the transmission of only certain bands of light.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The optical window runs from around 300 nm (ultraviolet-C) up into the range humans can see, the visible spectrum (commonly called light), at roughly 400–700 nm and continues to the infrared to around 1100 nm.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] There are also infrared and radio windows that transmit some infrared and radio waves at longer wavelengths.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] For example, the radio window runs from about one centimetre to about eleven-metre waves.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Because of its temperature, the atmosphere emits infrared radiation.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] For example, on clear nights Earth's surface cools down faster than on cloudy nights.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] This is because clouds (H2O) are strong absorbers and emitters of infrared radiation.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] This is also why it becomes colder at night at higher elevations.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The greenhouse effect is directly related to this absorption and emission effect.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Some gases in the atmosphere absorb and emit infrared radiation, but do not interact in this manner with sunlight in the visible spectrum.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Common examples of these are CO2 and H2O.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Without greenhouse gases in the atmosphere, the average temperature of Earth's surface would be a frozen −18 °C (0 °F), rather than the present comfortable average of 15 °C (59 °F).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The refractive index of air is close to, but just greater than, 1.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Systematic variations in the refractive index can lead to the bending of light rays over long optical paths.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] One example is that, under some circumstances, observers on board ships can see other vessels just over the horizon because light is refracted in the same direction as the curvature of Earth's surface.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The refractive index of air depends on temperature, giving rise to refraction effects when the temperature gradient is large.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] An example of such effects is the mirage.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The flow of air around the planet is divided into three main convection cells by latitude.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Around the equator, the Hadley cell is driven by the rising flow of air along the equator.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] In the upper atmosphere, this air flows toward the poles.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] At mid latitudes, this circulation is reversed, with ground air flowing toward the poles with the Ferrel cell.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Finally, in the high latitudes is the Polar cell, where air again rises and flows toward the poles.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The interface between these cells is responsible for jet streams.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] These are narrow, fast moving bands that flow from west to east and typically form at an elevation of around 9,100 m (30,000 ft).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Jet streams can shift around depending on conditions.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] They are strongest in winter, when the boundaries between hot and cold air are the most pronounced.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] In the middle latitudes, it is instabilities in the jet streams that are responsible for moving weather systems.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] As with the oceans, the Earth's atmosphere is subject to waves and tidal forces.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] These are triggered by non-uniform heating by the Sun, and by the daily solar cycle, respectively.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Wave-like behavior can occur on a variety of scales, from smaller gravity waves that transfer momentum into the higher atmospheric layers, to much larger planetary waves, or Rossby waves.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Atmospheric tides are periodic oscillations of the troposphere and stratosphere that transport energy to the upper atmosphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The first atmosphere, during the Early Earth's Hadean eon, consisted of gases in the solar nebula, primarily hydrogen, and probably simple hydrides such as those now found in the gas giants (Jupiter and Saturn), notably water vapor, methane and ammonia.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] During this earliest era, the Moon-forming collision and numerous impacts with large meteorites heated the atmosphere, driving off the most volatile gases.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The collision with Theia, in particular, melted and ejected large portions of Earth's mantle and crust and outgassed significant amounts of steam which eventually cooled and condensed to contribute to ocean water at the end of the Hadean.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The increasing solidification of Earth's crust at the end of the Hadean closed off most of the advective heat transfer to the surface, causing the atmosphere to cool, which condensed most of the water vapor out of the air precipitating into a superocean.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Further outgassing from volcanism, supplemented by gases introduced by huge asteroids during the Late Heavy Bombardment, created the subsequent Archean atmosphere, which consisted largely of nitrogen plus carbon dioxide, methane and inert gases.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] A major part of carbon dioxide emissions dissolved in water and reacted with metals such as calcium and magnesium during weathering of crustal rocks to form carbonates that were deposited as sediments.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Water-related sediments have been found that date from as early as 3.8 billion years ago.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] About 3.4 billion years ago, nitrogen formed the major component of the then-stable "second atmosphere".
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The influence of the evolution of life has to be taken into account rather soon in the history of the atmosphere because hints of earliest life forms appeared as early as 3.5 billion years ago.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] How Earth at that time maintained a climate warm enough for liquid water and life, if the early Sun put out 30% lower solar radiance than today, is a puzzle known as the "faint young Sun paradox".
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The geological record however shows a continuous relatively warm surface during the complete early temperature record of Earth – with the exception of one cold glacial phase about 2.4 billion years ago.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] In the late Neoarchean, an oxygen-containing atmosphere began to develop, apparently due to a billion years of cyanobacterial photosynthesis (known as the Great Oxygenation Event), which have been found as stromatolite fossils from 2.7 billion years ago.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The early basic carbon isotopy (isotope ratio proportions) strongly suggests conditions similar to the current, and that the fundamental features of the carbon cycle became established as early as 4 billion years ago.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Ancient sediments in the Gabon dating from between about 2.15 and 2.08 billion years ago provide a record of Earth's dynamic oxygenation evolution.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] These fluctuations in oxygenation were likely driven by the Lomagundi-Jatuli Carbon Isotope Excursion.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The constant re-arrangement of continents by plate tectonics influences the long-term evolution of the atmosphere by transferring carbon dioxide to and from large continental carbonate stores.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Before this time, any oxygen produced by cyanobacterial photosynthesis would be readily removed by the oxidation of reducing substances on the Earth's surface, notably ferrous iron, sulfur and atmospheric methane.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Free oxygen molecules did not start to accumulate in the atmosphere until the rate of production of oxygen began to exceed the availability of reductant materials that removed oxygen.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] This point signifies a shift from a reducing atmosphere to an oxidizing atmosphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] O2 showed major variations during the Proterozoic, including a billion-year period of euxinia, until reaching a steady state of more than 15% by the end of the Precambrian.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The amount of oxygen in the atmosphere has fluctuated over the last 600 million years, reaching a peak of about 35% around 280 million years ago during the Carboniferous period, significantly higher than today's 21%.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Two main processes govern changes in the atmosphere: the evolution of plants and their increasing role in carbon fixation, and the consumption of oxygen by rapidly diversifying animal faunae and also by plants for photorespiration and their own metabolic needs at night.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Breakdown of pyrite and volcanic eruptions release sulfur into the atmosphere, which reacts and hence reduces oxygen in the atmosphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] However, volcanic eruptions also release carbon dioxide, which can fuel oxygenic photosynthesis by terrestrial and aquatic plants.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] The cause of the variation of the amount of oxygen in the atmosphere is not precisely understood.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Periods with more oxygen in the atmosphere were often associated with more rapid development of animals.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Since 1750, human activity, especially after the Industrial Revolution, has increased the concentrations of various greenhouse gases, most importantly carbon dioxide, methane and nitrous oxide.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] Greenhouse gas emissions, coupled with deforestation and destruction of wetlands via logging and land developments, have caused an observed rise in global temperatures, with the global average surface temperatures being 1.1 °C higher in the 2011–2020 decade than they were in 1850.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/air] It has raised concerns of man-made climate change, which can have significant environmental impacts such as sea level rise, ocean acidification, glacial retreat (which threatens water security), increasing extreme weather events and wildfires, ecological collapse and mass dying of wildlife.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] In organic chemistry, an **alkane**, or **paraffin** (a historical trivial name that also has other meanings), is an acyclic saturated hydrocarbon.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] In other words, an alkane consists of hydrogen and carbon atoms arranged in a tree structure in which all the carbon–carbon bonds are single.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Alkanes have the general chemical formula C*n*H2*n*+2.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The alkanes range in complexity from the simplest case of methane (CH4), where *n* = 1 (sometimes called the parent molecule), to arbitrarily large and complex molecules, like hexacontane (C60H122) or 4-methyl-5-(1-methylethyl) octane, an isomer of dodecane (C12H26).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) defines alkanes as "acyclic branched or unbranched hydrocarbons having the general formula C*n*H2*n*+2, and therefore consisting entirely of hydrogen atoms and saturated carbon atoms".
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] However, some sources use the term to denote *any* saturated hydrocarbon, including those that are either monocyclic (i.e. the cycloalkanes) or polycyclic, despite them having a distinct general formula (e.g. cycloalkanes are C*n*H2*n*).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] In an alkane, each carbon atom is sp3-hybridized with 4 sigma bonds (either C–C or C–H), and each hydrogen atom is joined to one of the carbon atoms (in a C–H bond).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The longest series of linked carbon atoms in a molecule is known as its carbon skeleton or carbon backbone.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The number of carbon atoms may be considered as the size of the alkane.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] One group of the higher alkanes are waxes, solids at standard ambient temperature and pressure (SATP), for which the number of carbon atoms in the carbon backbone is greater than about 17.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Methane is produced by methanogenic archaea and some long-chain alkanes function as pheromones in certain animal species or as protective waxes in plants and fungi.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Nevertheless, most alkanes do not have much biological activity.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] They can be viewed as molecular trees upon which can be hung the more active/reactive functional groups of biological molecules.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The alkanes have two main commercial sources: petroleum (crude oil) and natural gas.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] An alkyl group is an alkane-based molecular fragment that bears one open valence for bonding.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] They are generally abbreviated with the symbol for any organyl group, R, although Alk is sometimes used to specifically symbolize an alkyl group (as opposed to an alkenyl group or aryl group).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Ordinarily, the C–C single bond distance is 1.53 ångströms (1.53×10−10 m).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Saturated hydrocarbons can be linear, branched, or cyclic.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The third group is sometimes called cycloalkanes.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Very complicated structures are possible by combining linear, branched, cyclic alkanes.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Alkanes with more than three carbon atoms can be arranged in various ways, forming structural isomers.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The simplest isomer of an alkane is the one in which the carbon atoms are arranged in a single chain with no branches.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] This isomer is sometimes called the *n*-isomer (*n* for "normal", although it is not necessarily the most common).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] However, the chain of carbon atoms may also be branched at one or more points.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The number of possible isomers increases rapidly with the number of carbon atoms.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] For example, 3-methylhexane and its higher homologues are chiral due to their stereogenic center at carbon atom number 3.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The above list only includes differences of connectivity, not stereochemistry.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] In addition to the alkane isomers, the chain of carbon atoms may form one or more rings.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Such compounds are called cycloalkanes, and are also excluded from the above list because changing the number of rings changes the molecular formula.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] For example, cyclobutane and methylcyclopropane are isomers of each other (C4H8), but are not isomers of butane (C4H10).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Branched alkanes are more thermodynamically stable than their linear (or less branched) isomers.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] For example, the highly branched 2,2,3,3-tetramethylbutane is about 1.9 kcal/mol more stable than its linear isomer, *n*-octane.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The IUPAC nomenclature (systematic way of naming compounds) for alkanes is based on identifying hydrocarbon chains.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Unbranched, saturated hydrocarbon chains are named systematically with a Greek numerical prefix denoting the number of carbons and the suffix "-ane".
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] In 1866, August Wilhelm von Hofmann suggested systematizing nomenclature by using the whole sequence of vowels a, e, i, o and u to create suffixes -ane, -ene, -ine (or -yne), -one, -une, for the hydrocarbons C*n*H2*n*+2, C*n*H2*n*, C*n*H2*n*−2, C*n*H2*n*−4, C*n*H2*n*−6.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] In modern nomenclature, the first three specifically name hydrocarbons with single, double and triple bonds; while "-one" now represents a ketone.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Straight-chain alkanes are sometimes indicated by the prefix *n*- (for "normal") where a non-linear isomer exists.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Alternative names for this group used in the petroleum industry are **linear paraffins** or ***n*-paraffins**.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The first four names were derived from methanol, ether, propionic acid and butyric acid.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Alkanes with five or more carbon atoms are named by adding the suffix **-ane** to the appropriate numerical multiplier prefix with elision of any terminal vowel (*-a* or *-o*) from the basic numerical term.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The numeral prefix is generally Greek; however, alkanes with a carbon atom count ending in nine, for example nonane, use the Latin prefix **non-**.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Simple branched alkanes often have a common name using a prefix to distinguish them from linear alkanes, for example *n*-butane, isobutane (or *i*-butane) for the two isomers of butane and *n*-pentane, isopentane, neopentane for the three isomers of pentane.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] IUPAC naming conventions can be used to produce a systematic name.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Though technically distinct from the alkanes, this class of hydrocarbons is referred to by some as the "cyclic alkanes." As their description implies, they contain one or more rings.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Simple cycloalkanes have a prefix "cyclo-" to distinguish them from alkanes.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Cycloalkanes are named as per their acyclic counterparts with respect to the number of carbon atoms in their backbones, e.g., cyclopentane (C5H10) is a cycloalkane with 5 carbon atoms just like pentane (C5H12), but they are joined up in a five-membered ring.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] In a similar manner, propane and cyclopropane, butane and cyclobutane, etc.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Substituted cycloalkanes are named similarly to substituted alkanes – the cycloalkane ring is stated, and the substituents are according to their position on the ring, with the numbering decided by the Cahn–Ingold–Prelog priority rules.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The trivial (non-systematic) name for alkanes is "paraffins".
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Together, alkanes are known as the "paraffin series".
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Trivial names for compounds are usually historical artifacts.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] They were coined before the development of systematic names, and have been retained due to familiar usage in industry.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Cycloalkanes are also called naphthenes.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Branched-chain alkanes are called **isoparaffins**.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] "Paraffin" is a general term and often does not distinguish between pure compounds and mixtures of isomers, i.e., compounds of the same chemical formula, e.g., pentane and isopentane.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Alkanes with the lowest molecular weights are gases, those of intermediate molecular weight are liquids, and the heaviest are waxy solids.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Alkanes experiences intermolecular van der Waals forces.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The cumulative effects of these intermolecular forces give rise to greater boiling points of alkanes.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Under standard conditions, from CH4 to C4H10 alkanes are gaseous; from C5H12 to C17H36 they are liquids; and after C18H38 they are solids.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] As the boiling point of alkanes is primarily determined by weight, it should not be a surprise that the boiling point has an almost linear relationship with the size (molecular weight) of the molecule.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] As a rule of thumb, the boiling point rises 20–30 °C for each carbon added to the chain; this rule applies to other homologous series.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] A straight-chain alkane will have a boiling point higher than a branched-chain alkane due to the greater surface area in contact, and thus greater van der Waals forces, between adjacent molecules.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] For example, compare isobutane (2-methylpropane) and *n*-butane, which boil at −12 and 0 °C, and 2,2-dimethylbutane and 2,3-dimethylbutane which boil at 50 and 58 °C, respectively.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] On the other hand, cycloalkanes tend to have higher boiling points than their linear counterparts due to the locked conformations of the molecules, which give a plane of intermolecular contact.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The melting points of the alkanes follow a similar trend to boiling points for the same reason as outlined above.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] That is, (all other things being equal) the larger the molecule the higher the melting point.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] However, alkanes' melting points follow a more complex pattern, due to variations in the properties of their solid crystals.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] One difference in crystal structure that even-numbered alkanes (from hexane onwards) tend to form denser-packed crystals compared to their odd-numbered neighbors.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] This causes them to have a greater enthalpy of fusion (amount of energy required to melt them), raising their melting point.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] A second difference in crystal structure is that even-numbered alkanes (from octane onwards) tend to form more rotationally ordered crystals compared to their odd-numbered neighbors.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] This causes them to have a greater entropy of fusion (increase in disorder from the solid to the liquid state), lowering their melting point.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] While these effects operate in opposing directions, the first effect tends to be slightly stronger, leading even-numbered alkanes to have slightly higher melting points than the average of their odd-numbered neighbors.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] This trend does not apply to methane, which has an unusually high melting point, higher than both ethane and propane.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] This is because it has a very low entropy of fusion, attributable to its high molecular symmetry and the rotational disorder in solid methane near its melting point (Methane I).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The melting points of branched-chain alkanes can be either higher or lower than those of the corresponding straight-chain alkanes, again depending on these two factors.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] More symmetric alkanes tend towards higher melting points, due to enthalpic effects when they form ordered crystals, and entropic effects when they form disordered crystals (e.g. neopentane).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Alkanes do not conduct electricity in any way, nor are they substantially polarized by an electric field.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] For this reason, they do not form hydrogen bonds and are insoluble in polar solvents such as water.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Since the hydrogen bonds between individual water molecules are aligned away from an alkane molecule, the coexistence of an alkane and water leads to an increase in molecular order (a reduction in entropy).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] As there is no significant bonding between water molecules and alkane molecules, the second law of thermodynamics suggests that this reduction in entropy should be minimized by minimizing the contact between alkane and water: Alkanes are said to be hydrophobic as they are insoluble in water.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Their solubility in nonpolar solvents is relatively high, a property that is called lipophilicity.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Alkanes are, for example, miscible in all proportions among themselves.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The density of the alkanes usually increases with the number of carbon atoms but remains less than that of water.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Hence, alkanes form the upper layer in an alkane–water mixture.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The molecular structure of the alkanes directly affects their physical and chemical characteristics.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] It is derived from the electron configuration of carbon, which has four valence electrons.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The carbon atoms in alkanes are described as sp3 hybrids; that is to say that, to a good approximation, the valence electrons are in orbitals directed towards the corners of a tetrahedron which are derived from the combination of the 2s orbital and the three 2p orbitals.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] This is exact for the case of methane, while larger alkanes containing a combination of C–H and C–C bonds generally have bonds that are within several degrees of this idealized value.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] An alkane has only C–H and C–C single bonds.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The former result from the overlap of an sp3 orbital of carbon with the 1s orbital of a hydrogen; the latter by the overlap of two sp3 orbitals on adjacent carbon atoms.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The bond lengths amount to 1.09 × 10−10 m for a C–H bond and 1.54 × 10−10 m for a C–C bond.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The spatial arrangement of the bonds is similar to that of the four sp3 orbitals—they are tetrahedrally arranged, with an angle of 109.47° between them.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Structural formulae that represent the bonds as being at right angles to one another, while both common and useful, do not accurately depict the geometry.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The spatial arrangement of the C-C and C-H bonds are described by the torsion angles of the molecule, known as its conformation.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] In ethane, the simplest case for studying the conformation of alkanes, there is nearly free rotation about a carbon–carbon single bond.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Two limiting conformations are important: eclipsed conformation and staggered conformation.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The staggered conformation is 12.6 kJ/mol (3.0 kcal/mol) lower in energy (more stable) than the eclipsed conformation (the least stable).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] In highly branched alkanes, the bond angle may differ from the optimal value (109.5°) to accommodate bulky groups.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Such distortions introduce a tension in the molecule, known as steric hindrance or strain.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Strain substantially increases reactivity.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Spectroscopic signatures for alkanes are obtainable by the major characterization techniques.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The C-H stretching mode gives strong absorptions between 2850 and 2960 cm−1 and weaker bands for the C-C stretching mode absorbs between 800 and 1300 cm−1.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The carbon–hydrogen bending modes depend on the nature of the group: methyl groups show bands at 1450 cm−1 and 1375 cm−1, while methylene groups show bands at 1465 cm−1 and 1450 cm−1.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Carbon chains with more than four carbon atoms show a weak absorption at around 725 cm−1.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The proton resonances of alkanes are usually found at *δ*H = 0.5–1.5.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The carbon-13 resonances depend on the number of hydrogen atoms attached to the carbon: *δ*C = 8–30 (primary, methyl, –CH3), 15–55 (secondary, methylene, –CH2–), 20–60 (tertiary, methyne, C–H) and quaternary.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The carbon-13 resonance of quaternary carbon atoms is characteristically weak, due to the lack of nuclear Overhauser effect and the long relaxation time, and can be missed in weak samples, or samples that have not been run for a sufficiently long time.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Since alkanes have high ionization energies, their electron impact mass spectra show weak currents for their molecular ions.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The fragmentation pattern can be difficult to interpret, but in the case of branched chain alkanes, the carbon chain is preferentially cleaved at tertiary or quaternary carbons due to the relative stability of the resulting free radicals.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The mass spectra for straight-chain alkanes is illustrated by that for dodecane: the fragment resulting from the loss of a single methyl group (*M* − 15) is absent, fragments are more intense than the molecular ion and are spaced by intervals of 14 mass units, corresponding to loss of CH2 groups.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Alkanes are only weakly reactive with most chemical compounds.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] They only react with the strongest of electrophilic reagents by virtue of their strong C–H bonds (~100 kcal/mol) and C–C bonds (~90 kcal/mol).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] They are also relatively unreactive toward free radicals.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] This inertness is the source of the term *paraffins* (with the meaning here of "lacking affinity").
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] In crude oil the alkane molecules have remained chemically unchanged for millions of years.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The acid dissociation constant (p*K*a) values of all alkanes are estimated to range from 50 to 70, depending on the extrapolation method, hence they are extremely weak acids that are practically inert to bases (see: carbon acids).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] They are also extremely weak bases, undergoing no observable protonation in pure sulfuric acid (*H*0 ~ −12), although superacids that are at least millions of times stronger have been known to protonate them to give hypercoordinate alkanium ions (see: methanium ion).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Thus, a mixture of antimony pentafluoride (SbF5) and fluorosulfonic acid (HSO3F), called magic acid, can protonate alkanes.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] All alkanes react with oxygen in a combustion reaction, although they become increasingly difficult to ignite as the number of carbon atoms increases.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] See the alkane heat of formation table for detailed data.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The standard enthalpy change of combustion, Δc*H*⊖, for alkanes increases by about 650 kJ/mol per CH2 group.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Branched-chain alkanes have lower values of Δc*H*⊖ than straight-chain alkanes of the same number of carbon atoms, and so can be seen to be somewhat more stable.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Some organisms are capable of metabolizing alkanes.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The methane monooxygenases convert methane to methanol.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] For higher alkanes, cytochrome P450 convert alkanes to alcohols, which are then susceptible to degradation.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Free radicals, molecules with unpaired electrons, play a large role in most reactions of alkanes.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Free radical halogenation reactions occur with halogens, leading to the production of haloalkanes.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The hydrogen atoms of the alkane are progressively replaced by halogen atoms.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The reaction of alkanes and fluorine is highly exothermic and can lead to an explosion.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] These reactions are an important industrial route to halogenated hydrocarbons.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Experiments have shown that all halogenation produces a mixture of all possible isomers, indicating that all hydrogen atoms are susceptible to reaction.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The mixture produced, however, is not statistical: Secondary and tertiary hydrogen atoms are preferentially replaced due to the greater stability of secondary and tertiary free-radicals.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] In the Reed reaction, sulfur dioxide and chlorine convert hydrocarbons to sulfonyl chlorides under the influence of light.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Under some conditions, alkanes will undergo nitration.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Certain transition metal complexes promote non-radical reactions with alkanes, resulting in C–H bond activation reactions.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Cracking breaks larger molecules into smaller ones.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] This reaction requires heat and catalysts.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The thermal cracking process follows a homolytic mechanism with formation of free radicals.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The catalytic cracking process involves the presence of acid catalysts (usually solid acids such as silica-alumina and zeolites), which promote a heterolytic (asymmetric) breakage of bonds yielding pairs of ions of opposite charges, usually a carbocation.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Carbon-localized free radicals and cations are both highly unstable and undergo processes of chain rearrangement, C–C scission in position beta (i.e., cracking) and intra- and intermolecular hydrogen transfer or hydride transfer.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] In both types of processes, the corresponding reactive intermediates (radicals, ions) are permanently regenerated, and thus they proceed by a self-propagating chain mechanism.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The chain of reactions is eventually terminated by radical or ion recombination.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Dragan and his colleague were the first to report about isomerization in alkanes.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Isomerization and reformation are processes in which straight-chain alkanes are heated in the presence of a platinum catalyst.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] In isomerization, the alkanes become branched-chain isomers.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] In other words, it does not lose any carbons or hydrogens, keeping the same molecular weight.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] In reformation, the alkanes become cycloalkanes or aromatic hydrocarbons, giving off hydrogen as a by-product.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Both of these processes raise the octane number of the substance.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Butane is the most common alkane that is put under the process of isomerization, as it makes many branched alkanes with high octane numbers.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] In steam reforming, alkanes react with steam in the presence of a nickel catalyst to give hydrogen and carbon monoxide.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Alkanes form a small portion of the atmospheres of the outer gas planets such as Jupiter (0.1% methane, 2 ppm ethane), Saturn (0.2% methane, 5 ppm ethane), Uranus (1.99% methane, 2.5 ppm ethane) and Neptune (1.5% methane, 1.5 ppm ethane).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Titan (1.6% methane), a satellite of Saturn, was examined by the *Huygens* probe, which indicated that Titan's atmosphere periodically rains liquid methane onto the moon's surface.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Also on Titan, the Cassini mission has imaged seasonal methane/ethane lakes near the polar regions of Titan.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Methane and ethane have been detected in the tail of the comet Hyakutake.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Chemical analysis showed that the abundances of ethane and methane were roughly equal, which is thought to imply that its ices formed in interstellar space, away from the Sun, which would have evaporated these volatile molecules.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Alkanes have been detected in meteorites such as carbonaceous chondrites.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Traces of methane gas (about 0.0002% or 1745 ppb) occur in the Earth's atmosphere, produced primarily by methanogenic microorganisms, such as Archaea in the gut of ruminants.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The most important commercial sources for alkanes are natural gas and oil.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Natural gas contains primarily methane and ethane, with some propane and butane: oil is a mixture of liquid alkanes and other hydrocarbons.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] These hydrocarbons were formed when marine animals and plants (zooplankton and phytoplankton) died and sank to the bottom of ancient seas and were covered with sediments in an anoxic environment and converted over many millions of years at high temperatures and high pressure to their current form.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] These hydrocarbon deposits, collected in porous rocks trapped beneath impermeable cap rocks, comprise commercial oil fields.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] They have formed over millions of years and once exhausted cannot be readily replaced.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The depletion of these hydrocarbons reserves is the basis for what is known as the energy crisis.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Alkanes have a low solubility in water, so the content in the oceans is negligible; however, at high pressures and low temperatures (such as at the bottom of the oceans), methane can co-crystallize with water to form a solid methane clathrate (methane hydrate).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Although this cannot be commercially exploited at the present time, the amount of combustible energy of the known methane clathrate fields exceeds the energy content of all the natural gas and oil deposits put together.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Methane extracted from methane clathrate is, therefore, a candidate for future fuels.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Aside from petroleum and natural gas, alkanes occur significantly in nature only as methane, which is produced by some archaea by the process of methanogenesis.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] These organisms are found in the gut of termites and cows.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The methane is produced from carbon dioxide or other organic compounds.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] It is probable that our current deposits of natural gas were formed in a similar way.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Certain types of bacteria can metabolize alkanes: they prefer even-numbered carbon chains as they are easier to degrade than odd-numbered chains.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Alkanes play a negligible role in higher organisms, with rare exception.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Some yeasts, e.g., *Candida tropicale*, *Pichia* sp., *Rhodotorula* sp., can use alkanes as a source of carbon or energy.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The fungus *Amorphotheca resinae* prefers the longer-chain alkanes in aviation fuel, and can cause serious problems for aircraft in tropical regions.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] In plants, the solid long-chain alkanes are found in the plant cuticle and epicuticular wax of many species, but are only rarely major constituents.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] They protect the plant against water loss, prevent the leaching of important minerals by the rain, and protect against bacteria, fungi, and harmful insects.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The carbon chains in plant alkanes are usually odd-numbered, between 27 and 33 carbon atoms in length, and are made by the plants by decarboxylation of even-numbered fatty acids.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The exact composition of the layer of wax is not only species-dependent but also changes with the season and such environmental factors as lighting conditions, temperature or humidity.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The Jeffrey pine is noted for producing exceptionally high levels of *n*-heptane in its resin, for which reason its distillate was designated as the zero point for one octane rating.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Floral scents have also long been known to contain volatile alkane components, and *n*-nonane is a significant component in the scent of some roses.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Emission of gaseous and volatile alkanes such as ethane, pentane, and hexane by plants has also been documented at low levels, though they are not generally considered to be a major component of biogenic air pollution.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Alkanes are important as pheromones, chemical messenger materials, on which insects depend for communication.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] 7-methyltricosane and 9-methyltricosane are active for ladybird beetles (*Adalia bipunctata*).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The emerald ash borer (*Agrilus planipennis Fairmaire*) responds to 9-methylpentacosane.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Female Asian long-horned beetles *Anoplophora glabripennis*, which are very damaging, secrete 2-methyldocosane.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Waggle-dancing honey bees produce and release two alkanes, tricosane and pentacosane.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] One example, in which both plant and animal alkanes play a role, is the ecological relationship between the sand bee (*Andrena nigroaenea*) and the early spider orchid (*Ophrys sphegodes*); the latter is dependent for pollination on the former.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Sand bees use pheromones in order to identify a mate; in the case of *A. nigroaenea*, the females emit a mixture of tricosane (C23H48), pentacosane (C25H52) and heptacosane (C27H56) in the ratio 3:3:1, and males are attracted by specifically this odor.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The orchid takes advantage of this mating arrangement to get the male bee to collect and disseminate its pollen; parts of its flower not only resemble the appearance of sand bees but also produce large quantities of the three alkanes in the same ratio as female sand bees.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] As a result, numerous males are lured to the blooms and attempt to copulate with their imaginary partner: although this endeavor is not crowned with success for the bee, it allows the orchid to transfer its pollen, which will be dispersed after the departure of the frustrated male to other blooms.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The most important source of alkanes is natural gas and crude oil.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Alkanes are separated in an oil refinery by fractional distillation.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Another route to alkanes is hydrogenolysis, which entails cleavage of C-heteroatom bonds using hydrogen.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] In industry, the main substrates are organonitrogen and organosulfur impurities, i.e. the heteroatoms are N and S.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Hydrogenolysis can be applied to the conversion of virtually any functional group into hydrocarbons.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Substrates include haloalkanes, alcohols, aldehydes, ketones, carboxylic acids, etc.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Both hydrogenolysis and hydrogenation are practiced in refineries.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] They can be effected by using lithium aluminium hydride, Clemmenson reduction and other specialized routes.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Coal is a more traditional precursor to alkanes.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] A wide range of technologies have been intensively practiced for centuries.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Simply heating coal gives alkanes, leaving behind coke.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Relevant technologies include the Bergius process and coal liquefaction.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Partial combustion of coal and related solid organic compounds generates carbon monoxide, which can be hydrogenated using the Fischer–Tropsch process.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] This technology allows the synthesis of liquid hydrocarbons, including alkanes.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] This method is used to produce substitutes for petroleum distillates.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Rarely is there any interest in the synthesis of alkanes, since they are usually commercially available and less valued than virtually any precursor.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The best-known method is hydrogenation of alkenes.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Many C−X bonds can be converted to C−H bonds using lithium aluminium hydride, Clemmenson reduction, and other specialized routes.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Hydrolysis of alkyl Grignard reagents and alkyl organolithium reagents gives alkanes.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] The dominant use of alkanes is as fuels.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Propane and butane, easily liquified gases, are commonly known as liquified petroleum gas (LPG).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] From pentane to octane the alkanes are highly volatile liquids.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] They are used as fuels in internal combustion engines, as they vaporize easily on entry into the combustion chamber without forming droplets, which would impair the uniformity of the combustion.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Branched-chain alkanes are preferred as they are much less prone to premature ignition, which causes knocking, than their straight-chain homologues.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] This propensity to premature ignition is measured by the octane rating of the fuel, where 2,2,4-trimethylpentane (*isooctane*) has an arbitrary value of 100, and heptane has a value of zero.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Apart from their use as fuels, the middle alkanes are also good solvents for nonpolar substances.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Alkanes from nonane to, for instance, hexadecane (an alkane with sixteen carbon atoms) are liquids of higher viscosity, less and less suitable for use in gasoline.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] They form instead the major part of diesel and aviation fuel.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Diesel fuels are characterized by their cetane number, cetane being an old name for hexadecane.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] However, the higher melting points of these alkanes can cause problems at low temperatures and in polar regions, where the fuel becomes too thick to flow correctly.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] By the process of cracking, alkanes can be converted to alkenes.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Simple alkenes are precursors to polymers, such as polyethylene and polypropylene.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] When the cracking is taken to extremes, alkanes can be converted to carbon black, which is a significant tire component.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Chlorination of methane gives chloromethanes, which are used as solvents and building blocks for complex compounds.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Similarly treatment of methane with sulfur gives carbon disulfide.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Still other chemicals are prepared by reaction with sulfur trioxide and nitric oxide.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Some light hydrocarbons are used as aerosol sprays.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Alkanes from hexadecane upwards form the most important components of fuel oil and lubricating oil.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] In the latter function, they work at the same time as anti-corrosive agents, as their hydrophobic nature means that water cannot reach the metal surface.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Many solid alkanes find use as paraffin wax, for example, in candles.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] This should not be confused however with true wax, which consists primarily of esters.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Alkanes with a chain length of approximately 35 or more carbon atoms are found in bitumen, used, for example, in road surfacing.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] However, the higher alkanes have little value and are usually split into lower alkanes by cracking.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Alkanes are highly flammable, but they have low toxicities.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Methane "is toxicologically virtually inert".
[src:air-fuel-ratio/alkanes] Alkanes can be asphyxiants and narcotic.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] It is a trace gas in Earth's atmosphere at 428 parts per million (ppm), or about 0.043% (as of July 2025) having risen from pre-industrial levels of 280 ppm or about 0.028%.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Burning fossil fuels is the main cause of these increased CO2 concentrations, which are the primary cause of climate change.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Its concentration in Earth's pre-industrial atmosphere since late in the Precambrian was regulated by organisms and geological features.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Plants, algae and cyanobacteria use energy from sunlight to synthesize carbohydrates from carbon dioxide and water in a process called photosynthesis, which produces oxygen as a waste product.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] In turn, oxygen is consumed and CO2 is released as waste by all aerobic organisms when they metabolize organic compounds to produce energy by respiration.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is released from organic materials when they decay or combust, such as in forest fires.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] When carbon dioxide dissolves in water, it forms carbonate and mainly bicarbonate (HCO3–), which causes ocean acidification as atmospheric CO2 levels increase.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is 53% denser than dry air, but is long-lived and thoroughly mixes in the atmosphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] About half of excess CO2 emissions to the atmosphere are absorbed by land and ocean carbon sinks.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] These sinks can become saturated and are volatile, as decay and wildfires result in the CO2 being released back into the atmosphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] CO2, or the carbon it holds, is eventually sequestered (stored for the long term) in rocks and organic deposits like coal, petroleum and natural gas.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Nearly all CO2 produced by humans goes into the atmosphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Less than 1% of CO2 produced annually is put to commercial use, mostly in the fertilizer industry and in the oil and gas industry for enhanced oil recovery.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Other commercial applications include food and beverage production, metal fabrication, cooling, fire suppression and stimulating plant growth in greenhouses.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] The symmetry of a carbon dioxide molecule is linear and centrosymmetric at its equilibrium geometry.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] The length of the carbon–oxygen bond in carbon dioxide is 116.3 pm, noticeably shorter than the roughly 140 pm length of a typical single C–O bond, and shorter than most other C–O multiply bonded functional groups such as carbonyls.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Since it is centrosymmetric, the molecule has no electric dipole moment.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] As a linear triatomic molecule, CO2 has four vibrational modes as shown in the diagram.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] In the symmetric and the antisymmetric stretching modes, the atoms move along the axis of the molecule.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] There are two bending modes, which are degenerate, meaning that they have the same frequency and same energy, because of the symmetry of the molecule.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] When a molecule touches a surface or touches another molecule, the two bending modes can differ in frequency because the interaction is different for the two modes.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Some of the vibrational modes are observed in the infrared (IR) spectrum: the antisymmetric stretching mode at wavenumber 2349 cm−1 (wavelength 4.25 μm) and the degenerate pair of bending modes at 667 cm−1 (wavelength 15.0 μm).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] The symmetric stretching mode does not create an electric dipole so is not observed in IR spectroscopy, but it is detected in Raman spectroscopy at 1388 cm−1 (wavelength 7.20 μm), with a Fermi resonance doublet at 1285 cm−1.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] In the gas phase, carbon dioxide molecules undergo significant vibrational motions and do not keep a fixed structure.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] However, in a Coulomb explosion imaging experiment, an instantaneous image of the molecular structure can be deduced.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Such an experiment has been performed for carbon dioxide.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] The result of this experiment, and the conclusion of theoretical calculations based on an ab initio potential energy surface of the molecule, is that none of the molecules in the gas phase are ever exactly linear.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] This counter-intuitive result is trivially due to the fact that the nuclear motion volume element vanishes for linear geometries.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] This is so for all molecules except diatomic molecules.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is soluble in water, in which it reversibly forms H2CO3 (carbonic acid), which is a weak acid, because its ionization in water is incomplete.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Hence, the majority of the carbon dioxide is not converted into carbonic acid, but remains as CO2 molecules, not affecting the pH.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] The relative concentrations of CO2, H2CO3, and the deprotonated forms HCO3– (bicarbonate) and CO32– (carbonate) depend on the pH.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] As shown in a Bjerrum plot, in neutral or slightly alkaline water (pH > 6.5), the bicarbonate form predominates (>50%) becoming the most prevalent (>95%) at the pH of seawater.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] In very alkaline water (pH > 10.4), the predominant (>50%) form is carbonate.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] The oceans, being mildly alkaline with typical pH = 8.2–8.5, contain about 120 mg of bicarbonate per liter.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] where the denominator includes only covalently bound H2CO3 and does not include hydrated CO2(aq).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Since most of the dissolved CO2 remains as CO2 molecules, *K*a1(apparent) has a much larger denominator and a much smaller value than the true *K*a1.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] The bicarbonate ion is an amphoteric species that can act as an acid or as a base, depending on pH of the solution.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] In organisms, carbonic acid production is catalysed by the enzyme known as carbonic anhydrase.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] In addition to altering its acidity, the presence of carbon dioxide in water also affects its electrical properties.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] When carbon dioxide dissolves in desalinated water, the electrical conductivity increases significantly from below 1 μS/cm to nearly 30 μS/cm.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] When heated, the water begins to gradually lose the conductivity induced by the presence of $\mathrm {CO_{2}}$ , especially noticeable as temperatures exceed 30 °C.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] The temperature dependence of the electrical conductivity of fully deionized water without CO2 saturation is comparably low in relation to these data.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is a potent electrophile having an electrophilic reactivity that is comparable to benzaldehyde or strongly electrophilic α,β-unsaturated carbonyl compounds.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] However, unlike electrophiles of similar reactivity, the reactions of nucleophiles with CO2 are thermodynamically less favored and are often found to be highly reversible.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] The reversible reaction of carbon dioxide with amines to make carbamates is used in CO2 scrubbers and has been suggested as a possible starting point for carbon capture and storage by amine gas treating.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] In metal carbon dioxide complexes, CO2 serves as a ligand, which can facilitate the conversion of CO2 to other chemicals.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] The redox potential for this reaction near pH 7 is about −0.53 V *versus* the standard hydrogen electrode.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] The nickel-containing enzyme carbon monoxide dehydrogenase catalyses this process.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] At low concentrations, the gas is odorless; however, at sufficiently high concentrations, it has a sharp, acidic odor.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] At standard temperature and pressure, the density of carbon dioxide is around 1.98 kg/m3, about 1.53 times that of air.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] At a pressure of 1 atm (0.101325 MPa), the gas deposits directly to a solid at temperatures below 194.6855(30) K (−78.4645(30) °C) and the solid sublimes directly to a gas above this temperature.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] In its solid state, carbon dioxide is commonly called dry ice.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Another form of solid carbon dioxide observed at high pressure is an amorphous glass-like solid.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] This form of glass, called *carbonia*, is produced by supercooling heated CO2 at extreme pressures (40–48 GPa, or about 400,000 atmospheres) in a diamond anvil.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] This discovery confirmed the theory that carbon dioxide could exist in a glass state similar to other members of its elemental family, like silicon dioxide (silica glass) and germanium dioxide.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Unlike silica and germania glasses, however, carbonia glass is not stable at normal pressures and reverts to gas when pressure is released.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] At temperatures and pressures above the critical point, carbon dioxide behaves as a supercritical fluid known as supercritical carbon dioxide.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is an end product of cellular respiration in organisms that obtain energy by breaking down sugars, fats and amino acids with oxygen as part of their metabolism.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] This includes all plants, algae and animals and aerobic fungi and bacteria.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] In vertebrates, the carbon dioxide travels in the blood from the body's tissues to the skin (e.g., amphibians) or the gills (e.g., fish), from where it dissolves in the water, or to the lungs from where it is exhaled.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] During active photosynthesis, plants can absorb more carbon dioxide from the atmosphere than they release in respiration.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Carbon fixation is a biochemical process by which atmospheric carbon dioxide is incorporated by plants, algae and cyanobacteria into energy-rich organic molecules such as glucose, thus creating their own food by photosynthesis.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Photosynthesis uses carbon dioxide and water to produce sugars from which other organic compounds can be constructed, and oxygen is produced as a by-product.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Ribulose-1,5-bisphosphate carboxylase oxygenase, commonly abbreviated to RuBisCO, is the enzyme involved in the first major step of carbon fixation, the production of two molecules of 3-phosphoglycerate from CO2 and ribulose bisphosphate, as shown in the diagram at left.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] RuBisCO is thought to be the single most abundant protein on Earth.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Phototrophs use the products of their photosynthesis as internal food sources and as raw material for the biosynthesis of more complex organic molecules, such as polysaccharides, nucleic acids, and proteins.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] These are used for their own growth, and also as the basis of the food chains and webs that feed other organisms, including animals such as ourselves.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Some important phototrophs, the coccolithophores synthesise hard calcium carbonate scales.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] A globally significant species of coccolithophore is *Emiliania huxleyi* whose calcite scales have formed the basis of many sedimentary rocks such as limestone, where what was previously atmospheric carbon can remain fixed for geological timescales.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Plants can grow as much as 50% faster in concentrations of 1,000 ppm CO2 when compared with ambient conditions, though this assumes no change in climate and no limitation on other nutrients.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Elevated CO2 levels cause increased growth reflected in the harvestable yield of crops, with wheat, rice and soybean all showing increases in yield of 12–14% under elevated CO2 in FACE experiments.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Increased atmospheric CO2 concentrations result in fewer stomata developing on plants which leads to reduced water usage and increased water-use efficiency.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Studies using FACE have shown that CO2 enrichment leads to decreased concentrations of micronutrients in crop plants.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] This may have knock-on effects on other parts of ecosystems as herbivores will need to eat more food to gain the same amount of protein.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] The concentration of secondary metabolites such as phenylpropanoids and flavonoids can also be altered in plants exposed to high concentrations of CO2.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Plants also emit CO2 during respiration, and so the majority of plants and algae, which use C3 photosynthesis, are only net absorbers during the day.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Though a growing forest will absorb many tons of CO2 each year, a mature forest will produce as much CO2 from respiration and decomposition of dead specimens (e.g., fallen branches) as is used in photosynthesis in growing plants.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Contrary to the long-standing view that they are carbon neutral, mature forests can continue to accumulate carbon and remain valuable carbon sinks, helping to maintain the carbon balance of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Additionally, and crucially to life on earth, photosynthesis by phytoplankton consumes dissolved CO2 in the upper ocean and thereby promotes the absorption of CO2 from the atmosphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide content in fresh air (averaged between sea-level and 10 kPa level, i.e., about 30 km (19 mi) altitude) varies between 0.036% (360 ppm) and 0.041% (412 ppm), depending on the location.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] In humans, exposure to CO2 at concentrations greater than 5% causes the development of hypercapnia and respiratory acidosis.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations of 7% to 10% (70,000 to 100,000 ppm) may cause suffocation, even in the presence of sufficient oxygen, manifesting as dizziness, headache, visual and hearing dysfunction, and unconsciousness within a few minutes to an hour.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations of more than 10% may cause convulsions, coma, and death.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] CO2 levels of more than 30% act rapidly leading to loss of consciousness in seconds.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Carrion feeders attracted to the carcasses are then also killed.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Children have been killed in the same way near the city of Goma by CO2 emissions from the nearby volcano Mount Nyiragongo.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] The Swahili term for this phenomenon is *mazuku*.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Adaptation to increased concentrations of CO2 occurs in humans, including modified breathing and kidney bicarbonate production, in order to balance the effects of blood acidification (acidosis).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Several studies suggested that 2.0 percent inspired concentrations could be used for closed air spaces (e.g. a submarine) since the adaptation is physiological and reversible, as deterioration in performance or in normal physical activity does not happen at this level of exposure for five days.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Yet, other studies show a decrease in cognitive function even at much lower levels.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Also, with ongoing respiratory acidosis, adaptation or compensatory mechanisms will be unable to reverse the condition.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] There are few studies of the health effects of long-term continuous CO2 exposure on humans and animals at levels below 1%.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Occupational CO2 exposure limits have been set in the United States at 0.5% (5000 ppm) for an eight-hour period.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] At this CO2 concentration, International Space Station crew experienced headaches, lethargy, mental slowness, emotional irritation, and sleep disruption.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Studies in animals at 0.5% CO2 have demonstrated kidney calcification and bone loss after eight weeks of exposure.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] A study of humans exposed in 2.5 hour sessions demonstrated significant negative effects on cognitive abilities at concentrations as low as 0.1% (1000 ppm) CO2 likely due to CO2 induced increases in cerebral blood flow.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Another study observed a decline in basic activity level and information usage at 1000 ppm, when compared to 500 ppm.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] However a review of the literature found that a reliable subset of studies on the phenomenon of carbon dioxide induced cognitive impairment to only show a small effect on high-level decision making (for concentrations below 5000 ppm).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Most of the studies were confounded by inadequate study designs, environmental comfort, uncertainties in exposure doses and differing cognitive assessments used.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Similarly a study on the effects of the concentration of CO2 in motorcycle helmets has been criticized for having dubious methodology in not noting the self-reports of motorcycle riders and taking measurements using mannequins.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Further when normal motorcycle conditions were achieved (such as highway or city speeds) or the visor was raised the concentration of CO2 declined to safe levels (0.2%).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Poor ventilation is one of the main causes of excessive CO2 concentrations in closed spaces, leading to poor indoor air quality.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide differential above outdoor concentrations at steady state conditions (when the occupancy and ventilation system operation are sufficiently long that CO2 concentration has stabilized) are sometimes used to estimate ventilation rates per person.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Higher CO2 concentrations are associated with occupant health, comfort and performance degradation.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] ASHRAE Standard 62.1–2007 ventilation rates may result in indoor concentrations up to 2,100 ppm above ambient outdoor conditions.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Thus if the outdoor concentration is 400 ppm, indoor concentrations may reach 2,500 ppm with ventilation rates that meet this industry consensus standard.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations in poorly ventilated spaces can be found even higher than this (range of 3,000 or 4,000 ppm).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Miners, who are particularly vulnerable to gas exposure due to insufficient ventilation, referred to mixtures of carbon dioxide and nitrogen as "blackdamp", "choke damp" or "stythe".
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Before more effective technologies were developed, miners would frequently monitor for dangerous levels of blackdamp and other gases in mine shafts by bringing a caged canary with them as they worked.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] The canary is more sensitive to asphyxiant gases than humans, and as it became unconscious would stop singing and fall off its perch.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] The Davy lamp could also detect high levels of blackdamp (which sinks, and collects near the floor) by burning less brightly, while methane, another suffocating gas and explosion risk, would make the lamp burn more brightly.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] In February 2020, three people died from suffocation at a party in Moscow when dry ice (frozen CO2) was added to a swimming pool to cool it down.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] A similar accident occurred in 2018 when a woman died from CO2 fumes emanating from the large amount of dry ice she was transporting in her car.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Humans spend more and more time in a confined atmosphere (around 80-90% of the time in a building or vehicle).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] In homes, schools, nurseries and offices, there are no systematic relationships between the levels of CO2 and other pollutants, and indoor CO2 is statistically not a good predictor of pollutants linked to outdoor road (or air, etc.) traffic.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is the parameter that changes the fastest (with hygrometry and oxygen levels when humans or animals are gathered in a closed or poorly ventilated room).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] In poor countries, many open hearths are sources of CO2 and CO emitted directly into the living environment.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Local concentrations of carbon dioxide can reach high values near strong sources, especially those that are isolated by surrounding terrain.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] At the Bossoleto hot spring near Rapolano Terme in Tuscany, Italy, situated in a bowl-shaped depression about 100 m (330 ft) in diameter, concentrations of CO2 rise to above 75% overnight, sufficient to kill insects and small animals.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] After sunrise the gas is dispersed by convection.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] High concentrations of CO2 produced by disturbance of deep lake water saturated with CO2 are thought to have caused 37 fatalities at Lake Monoun, Cameroon in 1984 and 1700 casualties at Lake Nyos, Cameroon in 1986.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] The body produces approximately 2.3 pounds (1.0 kg) of carbon dioxide per day per person, containing 0.63 pounds (290 g) of carbon.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] In humans, this carbon dioxide is carried through the venous system and is breathed out through the lungs, resulting in lower concentrations in the arteries.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] The carbon dioxide content of the blood is often given as the partial pressure, which is the pressure which carbon dioxide would have had if it alone occupied the volume.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] In humans, the blood carbon dioxide contents are shown in the adjacent table.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] CO2 is carried in blood in three different ways.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Exact percentages vary between arterial and venous blood.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Hemoglobin, the main oxygen-carrying molecule in red blood cells, carries both oxygen and carbon dioxide.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] However, the CO2 bound to hemoglobin does not bind to the same site as oxygen.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Instead, it combines with the N-terminal groups on the four globin chains.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] However, because of allosteric effects on the hemoglobin molecule, the binding of CO2 decreases the amount of oxygen that is bound for a given partial pressure of oxygen.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] This is known as the Haldane Effect, and is important in the transport of carbon dioxide from the tissues to the lungs.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Conversely, a rise in the partial pressure of CO2 or a lower pH will cause offloading of oxygen from hemoglobin, which is known as the Bohr effect.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is one of the mediators of local autoregulation of blood supply.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] If its concentration is high, the capillaries expand to allow a greater blood flow to that tissue.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Bicarbonate ions are crucial for regulating blood pH.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] A person's breathing rate influences the level of CO2 in their blood.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Breathing that is too slow or shallow causes respiratory acidosis, while breathing that is too rapid leads to hyperventilation, which can cause respiratory alkalosis.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Although the body requires oxygen for metabolism, low oxygen levels normally do not stimulate breathing.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Rather, breathing is stimulated by higher carbon dioxide levels.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] As a result, breathing low-pressure air or a gas mixture with no oxygen at all (such as pure nitrogen) can lead to loss of consciousness without ever experiencing air hunger.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] This is especially perilous for high-altitude fighter pilots.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] It is also why flight attendants instruct passengers, in case of loss of cabin pressure, to apply the oxygen mask to themselves first before helping others; otherwise, one risks losing consciousness.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] The respiratory centers try to maintain an arterial CO2 pressure of 40 mmHg.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] With intentional hyperventilation, the CO2 content of arterial blood may be lowered to 10–20 mmHg (the oxygen content of the blood is little affected), and the respiratory drive is diminished.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] This is why one can hold one's breath longer after hyperventilating than without hyperventilating.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] This carries the risk that unconsciousness may result before the need to breathe becomes overwhelming, which is why hyperventilation is particularly dangerous before free diving.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] In the atmosphere of Earth, carbon dioxide (CO2) is a trace gas that plays an integral part in the greenhouse effect, carbon cycle, photosynthesis, and oceanic carbon cycle.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] It is one of three main greenhouse gases in the atmosphere of Earth.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] In 2026, the concentration of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere reached 432 ppm or 0.0432% (on a molar basis), representing a mass of 3380 gigatonnes.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] This is an increase of 54% since the start of the Industrial Revolution, up from 280 ppm during the 10,000 years prior to the mid-18th century.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] The current increase in CO2 concentrations is primarily driven by the burning of fossil fuels.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Other significant human activities that emit CO2 include cement production, deforestation, and biomass burning.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] The increase in atmospheric concentrations of CO2 and other long-lived greenhouse gases such as methane increase the absorption and emission of infrared radiation by the atmosphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] This has led to a rise in average global temperature and ocean acidification.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Another direct effect is the CO2 fertilization effect.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] The increase in atmospheric concentrations of CO2 causes a range of further effects of climate change on the environment and human living conditions.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] It absorbs and emits infrared radiation at its two infrared-active vibrational frequencies.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] The two wavelengths are 4.26 μm (2,347 cm−1) (antisymmetric stretching vibrational mode) and 14.99 μm (667 cm−1) (bending vibrational mode).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] CO2 plays a significant role in influencing Earth's surface temperature through the greenhouse effect.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Light emission from the Earth's surface is most intense in the infrared region between 200 and 2500 cm−1, as opposed to light emission from the much hotter Sun which is most intense in the visible region.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Absorption of infrared light at the vibrational frequencies of atmospheric CO2 traps energy near the surface, warming the surface of Earth and its lower atmosphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Less energy reaches the upper atmosphere, which is therefore cooler because of this absorption.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] The present atmospheric concentration of CO2 is the highest for 14 million years.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Concentrations of CO2 in the atmosphere were as high as 4,000 ppm during the Cambrian period about 500 million years ago, and as low as 180 ppm during the Quaternary glaciation of the last two million years.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Reconstructed temperature records for the last 420 million years indicate that atmospheric CO2 concentrations peaked at approximately 2,000 ppm.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] This peak happened during the Devonian period (400 million years ago).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Another peak occurred in the Triassic period (220–200 million years ago).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide dissolves in the ocean to form carbonic acid (H2CO3), bicarbonate (HCO3–), and carbonate (CO32–).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] There is about fifty times as much carbon dioxide dissolved in the oceans as exists in the atmosphere.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] The oceans act as an enormous carbon sink, and have taken up about a third of CO2 emitted by human activity.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Ocean acidification is the ongoing decrease in the pH of the Earth's ocean.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Between 1950 and 2020, the average pH of the ocean surface fell from approximately 8.15 to 8.05.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide emissions from human activities are the primary cause of ocean acidification, with atmospheric carbon dioxide (CO2) levels exceeding 422 ppm (as of 2024).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] CO2 from the atmosphere is absorbed by the oceans.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] This chemical reaction produces carbonic acid (H2CO3) which dissociates into a bicarbonate ion (HCO−3) and a hydrogen ion (H+).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] The presence of free hydrogen ions (H+) lowers the pH of the ocean, increasing acidity (this does not mean that seawater is acidic yet; it is still alkaline, with a pH higher than 8).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Marine calcifying organisms, such as mollusks and corals, are especially vulnerable because they rely on calcium carbonate to build shells and skeletons.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] A change in pH by 0.1 represents a 26% increase in hydrogen ion concentration in the world's oceans (the pH scale is logarithmic, so a change of one in pH units is equivalent to a tenfold change in hydrogen ion concentration).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Sea-surface pH and carbonate saturation states vary depending on ocean depth and location.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Colder and higher latitude waters are capable of absorbing more CO2.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] This can cause acidity to rise, lowering the pH and carbonate saturation levels in these areas.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Several other factors influence the atmosphere-ocean CO2 exchange, and thus local ocean acidification.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] These include ocean currents and upwelling zones, proximity to large continental rivers, sea ice coverage, and atmospheric exchange with nitrogen and sulfur from fossil fuel burning and agriculture.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Changes in ocean chemistry can have extensive direct and indirect effects on organisms and their habitats.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] One of the most important repercussions of increasing ocean acidity relates to the production of shells out of calcium carbonate (CaCO3).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] This process is called calcification and is important to the biology and survival of a wide range of marine organisms.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Calcification involves the precipitation of dissolved ions into solid CaCO3 structures, structures for many marine organisms, such as coccolithophores, foraminifera, crustaceans, mollusks, etc.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] After they are formed, these CaCO3 structures are vulnerable to dissolution unless the surrounding seawater contains saturating concentrations of carbonate ions (CO2−3).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Very little of the extra carbon dioxide that is added into the ocean remains as dissolved carbon dioxide.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] The majority dissociates into additional bicarbonate and free hydrogen ions.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] To maintain chemical equilibrium, some of the carbonate ions already in the ocean combine with some of the hydrogen ions to make further bicarbonate.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] Carbon dioxide is also introduced into the oceans through hydrothermal vents.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] The *Champagne* hydrothermal vent, found at the Northwest Eifuku volcano in the Mariana Trench, produces almost pure liquid carbon dioxide, one of only two known sites in the world as of 2004, the other being in the Okinawa Trough.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carbon-dioxide] The finding of a submarine lake of liquid carbon dioxide in the Okinawa Trough was reported in 2006.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] A **carburetor** (also spelled **carburettor** or **carburetter**) is a device used by a gasoline internal combustion engine to control and mix air and fuel entering the engine.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] The primary method of adding fuel to the intake air is through the Venturi effect or Bernoulli's principle or with a pitot tube in the main metering circuit, though various other components are also used to provide extra fuel or air in specific circumstances.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Since the 1990s, carburetors have been largely replaced by fuel injection for cars and trucks, but carburetors are still used by some small engines (e.g. lawnmowers, generators, and concrete mixers) and motorcycles.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] In addition, they are still widely used on piston-engine–driven aircraft.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Diesel engines have always used fuel injection instead of carburetors, as they do not compress an air-fuel mix and instead require fuel injection much later in the compression stroke.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] The term "carburetor" is derived from the English verb *carburet*, meaning "to charge with hydrocarbons"; in early motoring books the product of the carburetor is *carburetted air*, i.e. air charged with hydrocarbon vapour.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] This meaning superseded that from the late eighteenth century in which *carburet* was a noun for which we now use the word *carbide*.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] A carburetor charges the intake air with vapour from a hydrocarbon-based fuel, such as petrol or autogas.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] The name is spelled "carburetor" in American English and "carburettor" in British English.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Colloquial abbreviations include "carb" in the UK and North America or "carby" in Australia.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Air from the atmosphere enters the carburetor (usually via an air cleaner), has fuel added within the carburetor, then the air fuel mixture leaves the carburetor and enters the inlet manifold, then through the inlet valve(s), and finally into the combustion chamber.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Most engines use a single carburetor shared among all of the cylinders, though some high-performance engines historically had multiple carburetors and/or throats.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] If the tube is a constant diameter the configuration is slightly simpler than in the cross-section diagram shown above right.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] In most cases (except for the *accelerator pump*), the driver pressing the throttle pedal does not directly increase the fuel entering the engine.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Instead, the airflow through the carburetor increases, which in turn increases the amount of fuel drawn into the intake mixture.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] If the pressure reduction is taken as from a reduction of area along the air flow rather than from ambient pressure to the fuel entry point the effect can be described as the Venturi effect, but that is still derived from Bernoulli's principle at two positions.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] If the pressure reduction is taken as from a dynamic pressure (facing the incoming air) within the air entry point rather than from ambient pressure instead the carbureter can be described as the Pitot tube type, but that is also still derived from Bernoulli's principle at two positions.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] The actual fuel and air flows are more complicated and need correction.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] This might be done variously at lower speeds or higher speeds, or over the whole range by a variable emulsion device to add air to the fuel after the main jets/s.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Zenith-Stromberg) variable jet carburetors, it was mainly controlled by varying the jet size.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] The orientation of the carburetor is a key design consideration.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Older engines used **updraft** carburetors, where the air enters from below the carburetor and exits through the top.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] From the late 1930s, **downdraft** carburetors become more commonly used (especially in the United States), along with **side draft** carburetors (especially in Europe).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] The main metering circuit usually consists of barrel/s which reduces to a narrow part where the air is at its highest speed, forming a choke or venturi.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Fuel is usually introduced into the air stream at that narrow part through small tubes leading from the main jet.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] The change in area is only necessary for a Venturi carburetor but in other configurations the barrel/s can be of constant area with the fuel entry anywhere along it.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Downstream of a choke or venturi is a throttle (usually in the form of a butterfly valve) which is used to control the amount of air entering the carburetor.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] In a car, this throttle is usually mechanically connected to the vehicle's throttle pedal, which varies engine speed.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] At lesser throttle openings, the air speed may be insufficient to maintain the main fuel flow, so then the fuel may be supplied by the carburetor's idle and off-idle circuits usually near the narrow gap between the edge of the butterfly plate and the body to give sufficient local air speed.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] At greater throttle openings, the speed of air increases, which lowers the pressure of the air and draws more fuel into the airstream.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] At the same time, the reduced manifold vacuum results in less fuel flow through the idle and off-idle circuits.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] During cold weather fuel vaporizes less readily and tends to condense on the walls of the intake manifold, starving the cylinders of fuel and making cold starts difficult.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Additional fuel is required (for a given amount of air) to start and run the engine until it warms up, provided by a *choke valve*.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] While the engine is warming up the choke valve is partially closed, restricting the flow of air at the entrance to the carburetor.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] This increases the vacuum in the main metering circuit, causing more fuel to be supplied to the engine via the main jets.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Prior to the late 1950s the choke was manually operated by the driver, often using a lever or knob on the dashboard.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Since then, automatic chokes became more commonplace.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] These either use a bimetallic thermostat to automatically regulate the choke based on the temperature of the engine's coolant liquid, an electrical resistance heater to do so, or air drawn through a tube connected to an engine exhaust source.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] A choke left closed after the engine has warmed up increases the engine's fuel consumption and exhaust gas emissions, and causes the engine to run rough and lack power due to an over-rich fuel mixture.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] However, excessive fuel can flood an engine and prevent it from starting.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] To remove the excess fuel, many carburetors with automatic chokes allow it to be held open (by manually, depressing the accelerator pedal to the floor and briefly holding it there while cranking the starter) to allow extra air into the engine until the excess fuel is cleared out.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Another method used by carburetors to improve the operation of a cold engine is a *fast idle cam*, which is connected to the choke and prevents the throttle from closing fully while the choke is in operation.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] The resulting increase in idle speed provides a more stable idle for a cold engine (by better atomizing the cold fuel) and helps the engine warm up quicker.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] The system within a carburetor that meters fuel when the engine is running at low RPM.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] The idle circuit is generally activated by vacuum near the (near closed) throttle plate, where the air speed increases to cause a low-pressure area in the idle passage/port, thus causing fuel to flow through the idle jet.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] The idle jet is set at some constant value by the carburetor manufacturer, thus flowing a specified amount of fuel.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Many carburetors use an off-idle circuit, which includes an additional fuel jet which is briefly used as the throttle starts to open.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] This jet is located in a low-pressure area caused by the high air speed near the (partly closed) throttle.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] The additional fuel it provides is used to compensate for the reduced vacuum that occurs when the throttle is opened, thus smoothing the transition from the idle circuit to the main metering circuit.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] In a four-stroke engine it is often desirable to provide extra fuel to the engine at high loads (to increase the power output and reduce engine knocking).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] A 'power valve', which is a spring-loaded valve in the carburetor that is held shut by engine vacuum, is often used to do so.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] As the airflow through the carburetor increases, the reduced manifold vacuum pulls the power valve open, allowing more fuel into the main metering circuit.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] In a two-stroke engine, the carburetor power valve operates in the opposite manner: in most circumstances the valve allows extra fuel into the engine, then at a certain engine RPM it closes to reduce the fuel entering the engine.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] This is done in order to extend the engine's maximum RPM, since many two-stroke engines can temporarily achieve higher RPM with a leaner air-fuel ratio.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] This is not to be confused with the unrelated exhaust power valve arrangements used on two-stroke engines.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] A metering rod or step-up rod system is sometimes used as an alternative to a power valve in a four-stroke engine in order to supply extra fuel at high loads.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] One end of the rods is tapered, which sits in the main metering jets and acts as a valve for fuel flow in the jets.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] At high engine loads, the rods are lifted away from the jets (either mechanically or using manifold vacuum), increasing the volume of fuel flow through the jet.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] These systems have been used by the Rochester Quadrajet and in the 1950s Carter carburetors.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] While the main metering circuit can adequately supply fuel to the engine in steady-state conditions, the inertia of fuel (being higher than that of air) causes a temporary shortfall as the throttle is opened.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Therefore, an accelerator pump is often used to briefly provide extra fuel as the throttle is opened.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] When the driver presses the throttle pedal, a small piston or diaphragm pump injects extra fuel directly into the carburetor throat.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] The accelerator pump can also be used to "prime" an engine with extra fuel prior to attempting a cold start.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] In order to ensure an adequate supply at all times, carburetors include a reservoir of fuel, called a "float chamber" or "float bowl".
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Fuel is delivered to the float chamber by a fuel pump or by gravity with the fuel tank located higher than the carburetor.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] A floating inlet valve regulates the fuel entering the float chamber, assuring a constant level.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] In some small engines that may instead of a float chamber just use a fuel tank close below the carburetor and use the fuel suction to supply the fuel.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Unlike in a fuel injected engine, the fuel system in a carbureted engine is not pressurized.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] For engines where the intake air travelling through the carburetor is pressurized (such as where the carburetor is downstream of a supercharger) the entire carburetor must be contained in an airtight pressurized box to operate.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] However, this is not necessary where the carburetor is upstream of the supercharger.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Problems of fuel boiling and vapor lock can occur in carbureted engines, especially in hotter climates.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Since the float chamber is located close to the engine, heat from the engine (including for several hours after the engine is shut off) can cause the fuel to heat up to the point of vaporization.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] This causes air bubbles in the fuel (similar to the air bubbles that necessitate brake bleeding), which prevents the flow of fuel and is known as 'vapor lock'.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] If an engine must be operated when the carburetor is not in an upright orientation (for example in a chainsaw or airplane), a float chamber and gravity activated float valve would not be suitable.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Instead, a diaphragm chamber is typically used.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] This consists of a flexible diaphragm on one side of the fuel chamber, connected to a needle valve which regulates the fuel entering the chamber.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] As the flowrate of the air in the chamber (controlled by the throttling valve/butterfly valve) decreases, the diaphragm moves inward (downward), which closes the needle valve to admit less fuel.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] As the flowrate of the air in the chamber increases, the diaphragm moves outward (upward) which opens the needle valve to admit more fuel, allowing the engine to generate more power.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] A balanced state is reached which creates a steady fuel reservoir level, that remains constant in any orientation.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] The basic design for a carburetor consists of a single venturi (main metering circuit), though designs with two or four venturi (two-barrel and four-barrel carburetors respectively) are also quite commonplace.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Typically the barrels consist of "primary" barrel(s) used for lower load situations and secondary barrel(s) activating when required to provide additional air/fuel at higher loads.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] The primary and secondary venturi are often sized differently and incorporate different features to suit the situations in which they are used.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Many four-barrel carburetors use two primary and two secondary barrels.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] A four-barrel design of two primary and two secondary barrels was commonly used in V8 engines to conserve fuel at low engine speeds while still affording an adequate supply at high.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] The use of multiple carburetors (e.g., a carburetor for each cylinder or pair of cylinders) also results in the intake air being drawn through multiple venturi.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Some high-performance engines have used multiple two-barrel or four-barrel carburetors, for example six two-barrel carburetors on Ferrari V12s.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] In 1826, American engineer Samuel Morey received a patent for a "gas or vapor engine", which had a carburetor that mixed turpentine and air.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] In 1888/1889 German engineer Siegfried Marcus produced a car powered by a petrol engine (which also debuted the first magneto ignition system).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Karl Benz introduced his single-cylinder four-stroke powered Benz Patent-Motorwagen in 1885.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] All three of these engines used surface carburetors, which operated by moving air across the top of a vessel containing the fuel.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] The first float-fed carburetor design, which used an atomizer nozzle, was introduced by German engineers Wilhelm Maybach and Gottlieb Daimler in their 1885 *Grandfather Clock engine*.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] The Butler Petrol Cycle car—built in England in 1888—also used a float-fed carburetor.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] In 1892 Maybach produced an important carburetor with a jet spraying into a venturi, as would become the norm; this was patented in 1893.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] The first carburetor for a stationary engine was patented in 1893 by Hungarian engineers János Csonka and Donát Bánki.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] The first four-barrel carburetors were the Carter Carburetor WCFB and the identical Rochester 4GC, introduced in various General Motors models for 1952.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Oldsmobile referred the new carburetor as the "Quadri-Jet" (original spelling) while Buick called it the "Airpower".
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] In the United States, carburetors were the common method of fuel delivery for most US-made gasoline (petrol) engines until the late 1980s, when fuel injection became the preferred method.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] One of the last motorsport users of carburetors was NASCAR, which switched to electronic fuel injection after the 2011 Sprint Cup series.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] NASCAR still uses the four-barrel carburetor in the NASCAR Xfinity Series.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] In Europe, carburetors were largely replaced by fuel injection in the late 1980s, although fuel injection had been increasingly used in luxury cars and sports cars since the 1970s.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] EEC legislation required all vehicles sold and produced in member countries to have a catalytic converter after December 1992.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] This legislation had been in the pipeline for some time, with many cars becoming available with catalytic converters or fuel injection from around 1990.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] A significant concern for aircraft engines is the formation of ice inside the carburetor.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] The temperature of air within the carburetor can be reduced by up to 40 °C (72 °F), due to a combination of the reduced air pressure in the venturi and the latent heat of the evaporating fuel.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] The conditions during the descent to landing are particularly conducive to icing, since the engine is run at idle for a prolonged period with the throttle closed.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Icing can also occur in cruise conditions at altitude.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] A carburetor heat system is often used to prevent icing.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] This system consists of a secondary air intake which passes around the exhaust, in order to heat the air before it enters the carburetor.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Typically, the system is operated by the pilot manually switching the intake air to travel via the heated intake path as required.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] The carburetor heat system reduces the power output (due to the lower density of heated air) and causes the intake air filter to be bypassed, therefore the system is only used when there is a risk of icing.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] If the engine is operating at idle RPM, another method to prevent icing is to periodically open the throttle, which increases the air temperature within the carburetor.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Carburetor icing also occurs on other applications and various methods have been employed to solve this problem.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] On inline engines the intake and exhaust manifolds are on the same side of the head.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Heat from the exhaust is used to warm the intake manifold and in turn the carburetor.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] On V configurations, exhaust gases were directed from one head through the intake cross over to the other head.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] One method for regulating the exhaust flow on the cross over for intake warming was a weighted eccentric butterfly valve called a heat riser that remained closed at idle and opened at higher exhaust flow.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] Some vehicles used a heat stove around the exhaust manifold.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] It was connected to the air filter intake via tubing and supplied warmed air to the air filter.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/carburetor] A vacuum controlled butterfly valve pre heat tube on the intake horn of the air cleaner would open allowing cooler air when engine load increased.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] A **catalytic converter** is an exhaust emission control device which converts toxic gases and pollutants in exhaust gas from an internal combustion engine into less-toxic pollutants by catalyzing a redox reaction.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Catalytic converters are usually used with internal combustion engines fueled by gasoline (petrol) or diesel, including lean-burn engines, and sometimes on kerosene heaters and stoves.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] The first widespread introduction of catalytic converters was in the United States automobile market.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] To comply with the US Environmental Protection Agency's stricter regulation of exhaust emissions, most gasoline-powered vehicles starting with the 1975 model year are equipped with catalytic converters.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] These "two-way" oxidation converters combine oxygen with carbon monoxide (CO) and unburned hydrocarbons (HC) to produce carbon dioxide (CO2) and water (H2O).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] "Three-way" converters, which also reduce oxides of nitrogen (NO*x*), were first commercialized by Volvo on the California-specification 1977 240 cars.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] When U.S. federal emission control regulations began requiring tight control of NOx for the 1981 model year, most all automakers met the tighter standards with three-way catalytic converters and associated engine control systems.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Oxidation-only two-way converters are still used on lean-burn engines to oxidize particulate matter and hydrocarbon emissions (including diesel engines, which typically use lean combustion), as three-way-converters require fuel-rich or stoichiometric combustion to successfully reduce NO*x*.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Although catalytic converters are most commonly applied to exhaust systems in automobiles, they are also used on electrical generators, forklifts, mining equipment, trucks, buses, locomotives, motorcycles, and on ships.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Rarely, devices similar to catalytic converters are used in appliances such as wood stoves to control emissions.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Catalytic converter prototypes were first designed in France at the end of the 19th century, when only a few thousand "oil cars" were on the roads; these prototypes had inert clay-based materials coated with platinum, rhodium, and palladium and sealed into a double metallic cylinder.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] A few decades later, a catalytic converter was patented by Eugene Houdry, a French mechanical engineer.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Houdry was an expert in catalytic oil refining, having invented the catalytic cracking process that all modern refining is based on today.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Houdry moved to the United States in 1930 to live near the refineries in Philadelphia and develop his catalytic refining process.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] When the results of early studies of smog in Los Angeles were published, Houdry became concerned about the role of smokestack exhaust and automobile exhaust in air pollution and founded a company called Oxy-Catalyst.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Houdry first developed catalytic converters for smokestacks, and later developed catalytic converters for warehouse forklifts running on unleaded gasoline.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] In the mid-1950s, he began research to develop catalytic converters for gasoline engines used on cars and was awarded United States Patent 2,742,437 for his work.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Catalytic converters were further developed by a series of engineers including Carl D.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Mooney, Antonio Eleazar, and Phillip Messina at Engelhard Corporation, creating the first production catalytic converter in 1973.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Environmental Protection Agency's new exhaust emissions regulations, most gasoline-powered vehicles manufactured from 1975 onwards are equipped with catalytic converters.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Early catalytic converters were "two-way", combining oxygen with carbon monoxide (CO) and unburned hydrocarbons (HC, chemical compounds in fuel of the form CmHn) to produce carbon dioxide (CO2) and water (H2O).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] These stringent emission control regulations also resulted in the removal of the antiknock agent tetraethyl lead from automotive gasoline, to reduce lead in the air.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Lead and its compounds are catalyst poisons and foul catalytic converters by coating the catalyst's surface.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Requiring the removal of lead allowed the use of catalytic converters to meet the other emission standards in the regulations.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] To lower harmful NO*x* emissions, a twin-catalyst system was developed in the 1970s – this added a separate (rhodium/platinum) catalyst which reduced NO*x* ahead of the air pump, after which a two-way catalytic converter (palladium/platinum) removed HC and CO.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] This cumbersome and expensive system was soon made redundant, after it was noted that under some conditions the initial catalyst also removed HC and CO.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] This led to the development of the three-way catalyst, made possible by electronics and engine management developments.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Pfefferle developed a catalytic combustor for gas turbines in the early 1970s, allowing combustion without significant formation of nitrogen oxides and carbon monoxide.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Four-way catalytic converters have also been developed which also remove particulates from engine exhaust; since most of these particulates are unburned hydrocarbons, they can be burned to convert them into carbon dioxide.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] A washcoat is a carrier for the catalytic materials and is used to disperse the materials over a large surface area.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Aluminum oxide, titanium dioxide, silicon dioxide e.g. colloidal silica or a mixture of silica and alumina can be used.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] The catalytic materials are suspended in the washcoat prior to applying to the core.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Washcoat materials are selected to form a rough, irregular surface, which increases the surface area compared to the smooth surface of the bare substrate.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] These oxides are mainly added as oxygen storage promoters.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] The catalyst itself is most often a mix of precious metals, mostly from the platinum group.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Platinum is the most active catalyst and is widely used, but is not suitable for all applications because of unwanted additional reactions and historically high cost.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Palladium and rhodium are two other precious metals used, though as of February 2023, platinum has become the least expensive of the platinum group metals.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Rhodium is used as a reduction catalyst, palladium is used as an oxidation catalyst, and platinum is used both for reduction and oxidation.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Cerium, iron, manganese, and nickel are also used, although each has limitations.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Copper can also be used in most countries.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Nickel is not legal for use in the European Union because of its reaction with carbon monoxide into toxic nickel tetracarbonyl.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Upon failure, a catalytic converter can be recycled rather than being scrapped.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] The precious metals inside the converter – the platinum, palladium, and rhodium – are extracted.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Catalytic converters require a temperature of 400 °C (750 °F) to operate effectively.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Therefore, they are placed as close to the engine as possible, or one or more smaller catalytic converters (known as "pre-cats") are placed immediately after the exhaust manifold.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] The two-way catalytic converter is widely used on diesel engines to reduce hydrocarbon and carbon monoxide emissions.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] They were also used on gasoline engines in American and Canadian automobile markets until 1981.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Because of their inability to control oxides of nitrogen, manufacturers briefly installed twin catalyst systems, with an NO*x* reducing, rhodium/platinum catalyst ahead of the air pump, which led to the development of the three-way catalytic converter.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] The two-way catalytic converter also continued to be used on certain, lower-cost cars in some markets such as Europe, where NO*x* emissions were not universally regulated until the introduction of the Euro 3 emissions standard in 2000.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] The three-way catalytic converters have the additional advantage of controlling the emission of nitric oxide (NO) and nitrogen dioxide (NO2) (both together abbreviated with NO*x* and not to be confused with nitrous oxide (N2O)).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] NO*x* are precursors to acid rain and smog.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] The reduction and oxidation catalysts are typically contained in a common housing; however, in some instances, they may be housed separately.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] These three reactions occur most efficiently when the engine runs within a narrow band of air-fuel ratios near the stoichiometric point.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Total conversion efficiency falls very rapidly when the engine is operated outside of this band.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Slightly lean of stoichiometric, the exhaust gases from the engine contain excess oxygen, the production of NO*x* by the engine increases, and the efficiency of the catalyst at reducing NO*x* falls off rapidly.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] However, the conversion of HC and CO is very efficient due to the available oxygen, oxidizing to H2O and CO2.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Slightly rich of stoichiometric, the production of CO and unburnt HC by the engine starts to increase dramatically, available oxygen decreases, and the efficiency of the catalyst for oxidizing CO and HC decreases significantly, especially as stored oxygen becomes depleted.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] However, the efficiency of the catalyst at reducing NO*x* is good, and the production of NO*x* by the engine decreases.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] To maintain catalyst efficiency, the air–fuel ratio must stay close to stoichiometric and not remain rich or lean for too long.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Therefore, engines fitted with regulated 3-way catalytic converters have a closed-loop feedback carburetor or fuel injection engine control system to manage a continuous rich-lean balance required for effective NO*x* reduction and HC+CO oxidation.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] The control system allows the catalyst to release oxygen during slightly rich operating conditions, which oxidizes CO and HC under conditions that also favor the reduction of NOx.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Before the stored oxygen is depleted, the control system shifts the air-fuel ratio to become slightly lean, improving HC and CO oxidation while storing additional oxygen in the catalyst material, at a small penalty in NO*x* reduction efficiency.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Then the air–fuel mixture is brought back to slightly rich, at a small penalty in CO and HC oxidation efficiency, and the cycle repeats.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Efficiency is improved when this oscillation around the stoichiometric point is small and carefully controlled.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Closed-loop control under light to moderate load is accomplished by using one or more oxygen sensors in the exhaust system.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] When oxygen is detected by the sensor, the air-fuel ratio is lean of stoichiometric, and when oxygen is not detected, it is rich.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] The control system adjusts the amount of fuel being fed to the engine based on this signal to keep the air-fuel ratio near the stoichiometric point in order to maximize the catalyst conversion efficiency.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] The control algorithm is also affected by the time delay between the adjustment of the fuel flow rate and the sensing of the changed air–fuel ratio by the sensor, as well as the sigmoidal response of the oxygen sensors.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Typical control systems are designed to rapidly sweep the air–fuel ratio such that it oscillates slightly around the stoichiometric point, staying near the optimal efficiency point while managing the levels of stored oxygen and unburnt HC.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Closed-loop control is often suspended during high load/maximum power operation, when an increase in emissions is permitted and a rich mixture is commanded to increase power and prevent exhaust gas temperature from exceeding design limits.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] This presents a challenge for control system and catalyst design.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] During such operations, large amounts of unburnt HC are produced by the engine, well beyond the capacity of the catalyst to release oxygen.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] The surface of the catalyst quickly becomes saturated with HC.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] When returning to lower power output and leaner air-fuel ratios, the control system must prevent excessive oxygen from reaching the catalyst too quickly, as this will rapidly burn the HC in the already hot catalyst, potentially exceeding the design temperature limit of the catalyst.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Excessive catalyst temperature can prematurely age the catalyst, reducing its efficiency before reaching its design lifetime.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Excessive catalyst temperature can also be caused by cylinder misfire, which continuously flows unburnt HC combined with oxygen to the hot catalyst, burning in the catalyst and increasing its temperature.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Unwanted reactions result in the formation of hydrogen sulfide and ammonia, which poison catalysts.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Nickel or manganese is sometimes added to the washcoat to limit hydrogen-sulfide emissions.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Sulfur-free or low-sulfur fuels eliminate or minimize problems with hydrogen sulfide.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] For compression-ignition (i.e., diesel) engines, the most commonly used catalytic converter is the *diesel oxidation catalyst* (DOC).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] DOCs contain palladium or platinum supported on alumina.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] This catalyst converts particulate matter (PM), hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide to carbon dioxide and water.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] These converters often operate at 90 percent efficiency, virtually eliminating diesel odor and helping reduce visible particulates.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] These catalysts are ineffective for NO*x*, so NO*x* emissions from diesel engines are controlled by exhaust gas recirculation (EGR).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] In 2010, most light-duty diesel manufacturers in the U.S. added catalytic systems to their vehicles to meet federal emissions requirements.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Two techniques have been developed for the catalytic reduction of NO*x* emissions under lean exhaust conditions, selective catalytic reduction (SCR) and the NO*x* adsorber.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Instead of precious metal-containing NO*x* absorbers, most manufacturers selected base-metal SCR systems that use a reagent such as ammonia to reduce the NO*x* into nitrogen and water.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Ammonia is supplied to the catalyst system by the injection of urea into the exhaust, which then undergoes thermal decomposition and hydrolysis into ammonia.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] The urea solution is also referred to as diesel exhaust fluid (DEF).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Diesel exhaust contains relatively high levels of particulate matter.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Catalytic converters remove only 20–40% of PM so particulates are cleaned up by a soot trap or diesel particulate filter (DPF).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] In the U.S., all on-road light, medium, and heavy-duty diesel-powered vehicles built after 1 January 2007, are subject to diesel particulate emission limits, and so are equipped with a 2-way catalytic converter and a diesel particulate filter.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] As long as the engine was manufactured before 1 January 2007, the vehicle is not required to have the DPF system.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] This led to an inventory runup by engine manufacturers in late 2006 so they could continue selling pre-DPF vehicles well into 2007.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] For lean-burn spark-ignition engines, an oxidation catalyst is used in the same manner as in a diesel engine.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Emissions from lean burn spark ignition engines are very similar to emissions from a diesel compression ignition engine.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Many vehicles have a close-coupled catalytic converter located near the engine's exhaust manifold.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] The converter heats up quickly, due to its exposure to the very hot exhaust gases, allowing it to reduce undesirable emissions during the engine warm-up period.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] This is achieved by burning off the excess hydrocarbons which result from the extra-rich mixture required for a cold start.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] When catalytic converters were first introduced, most vehicles used carburetors that provided a relatively rich air-fuel ratio.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Oxygen (O2) levels in the exhaust stream were therefore generally insufficient for the catalytic reaction to occur efficiently.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Most designs of the time therefore included secondary air injection, which injected air into the exhaust stream.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] This increased the available oxygen, allowing the catalyst to function as intended.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Some three-way catalytic converter systems have air injection systems with the air injected between the first (NO*x* reduction) and second (HC and CO oxidation) stages of the converter.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] As in two-way converters, this injected air provides oxygen for the oxidation reactions.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] An upstream air injection point, ahead of the catalytic converter, is also sometimes present to provide additional oxygen only during the engine warm up period.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] This causes unburned fuel to ignite in the exhaust tract, thereby preventing it reaching the catalytic converter at all.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] This technique reduces the engine runtime needed for the catalytic converter to reach its "light-off" or operating temperature.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Most newer vehicles have electronic fuel injection systems, and do not require air injection systems in their exhausts.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Instead, they provide a precisely controlled air-fuel mixture that quickly and continually cycles between lean and rich combustion.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Catalyst poisoning occurs when the catalytic converter is exposed to exhaust containing substances that coat the working surfaces, so that they cannot contact and react with the exhaust.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] The most notable contaminant is lead, so vehicles equipped with catalytic converters can run only on unleaded fuel.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Other common catalyst poisons include sulfur, manganese (originating primarily from the gasoline additive MMT), and silicon, which can enter the exhaust stream if the engine has a leak that allows coolant into the combustion chamber.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Phosphorus is another catalyst contaminant.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Although phosphorus is no longer used in gasoline, it (and zinc, another low-level catalyst contaminant) was widely used in engine oil antiwear additives such as zinc dithiophosphate (ZDDP).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Beginning in 2004, a limit of phosphorus concentration in engine oils was adopted in the API SM and ILSAC GF-4 specifications.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Depending on the contaminant, catalyst poisoning can sometimes be reversed by running the engine under a very heavy load for an extended period of time.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] The increased exhaust temperature can sometimes vaporize or sublimate the contaminant, removing it from the catalytic surface.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] However, removal of lead deposits in this manner is usually not possible because of lead's high boiling point.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Oil and coolant leaks, perhaps caused by a head gasket leak, can also cause high unburned hydrocarbons.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Emissions regulations vary considerably from jurisdiction to jurisdiction.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Most automobile spark-ignition engines in North America have been fitted with catalytic converters since 1975, and the technology used in non-automotive applications is generally based on automotive technology.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] In many jurisdictions, it is illegal to remove or disable a catalytic converter for any reason other than its direct and immediate replacement.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Nevertheless, some vehicle owners remove or "gut" the catalytic converter on their vehicle.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] In such cases, the converter may be replaced by a welded-in section of ordinary pipe or a flanged "test pipe", ostensibly meant to check if the converter is clogged by comparing how the engine runs with and without the converter.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] This facilitates temporary reinstallation of the converter in order to pass an emission test.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Vehicles without functioning catalytic converters generally fail emission inspections.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] The automotive aftermarket supplies high-flow converters for vehicles with upgraded engines, or whose owners prefer an exhaust system with larger-than-stock capacity.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Catalytic converters have been mandatory on all new gasoline cars sold in the European Union and the United Kingdom since 1 January 1993 in order to comply with the Euro 1 emission standards.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Faulty catalytic converters as well as undamaged early types of converters can restrict the flow of exhaust, which negatively affects vehicle performance and fuel economy.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Modern catalytic converters do not significantly restrict exhaust flow.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] A 2006 test on a 1999 Honda Civic, for example, showed that removing the stock catalytic converter netted only a 3% increase in maximum horsepower; a new metallic core converter only cost the car 1% horsepower, compared to no converter.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Carburetors on pre-1981 vehicles without feedback fuel-air mixture control could easily provide too much fuel to the engine, which could cause the catalytic converter to overheat and potentially ignite flammable materials under the car.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Vehicles fitted with catalytic converters emit most of their total pollution during the first five minutes of engine operation; that is, before the catalytic converter has warmed up sufficiently to be fully effective.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] In the early 2000s it became common to place the catalyst converter right next to the exhaust manifold, close to the engine, for much quicker warm-up.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] In 1995, Alpina introduced an electrically heated catalyst.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Called "E-KAT", it was used in Alpina's B12 5,7 E-KAT based on the BMW 750i.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Heating coils inside the catalytic converter assemblies are electrified just after the engine is started, bringing the catalyst up to operating temperature very quickly to qualify the vehicle for low emission vehicle (LEV) designation.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] BMW later introduced the same heated catalyst, developed jointly by Emitec, Alpina, and BMW, in its 750i in 1999.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Some vehicles contain a pre-cat, a small catalytic converter upstream of the main catalytic converter which heats up faster on vehicle start up, reducing the emissions associated with cold starts.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] A pre-cat is most commonly used by an auto manufacturer when trying to attain the Ultra Low Emissions Vehicle (ULEV) rating, such as on the Toyota MR2 Roadster.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Catalytic converters have proven to be reliable and effective in reducing noxious tailpipe emissions.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Because of the external location and the use of valuable precious metals including platinum, palladium and rhodium, catalytic converters are a target for thieves.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] The problem is especially common among late-model pickup trucks and truck-based SUVs, because of their high ground clearance and easily removed bolt-on catalytic converters.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Welded-on converters are also at risk of theft, as they can be easily cut off.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Pipecutters are often used to quietly remove the converter but other tools such as a portable reciprocating saw can damage other components of the car, such as the oxygen sensor, wiring or fuel lines, with potentially dangerous consequences.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] In 2023, bipartisan legislation to combat catalytic converter theft was introduced in the U.S.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] The Preventing Auto Recycling Thefts Act (PART Act) would mandate catalytic converters in new vehicles to come with traceable identification numbers.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Additionally, the legislation would make catalytic converter theft a federal criminal offense.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Rising metal prices in the U.S. during the 2000s commodities boom led to a significant increase in converter theft.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] A catalytic converter can cost more than $1,000 to replace, more if the vehicle is damaged during the theft.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Apart from damaging other systems of the vehicle, theft can also cause death and injury to thieves.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Thefts of catalytic converters rose over tenfold in the United States from the late 2010s to early 2020s, driven presumably by the rise in the price of precious metals contained within the converters.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Study findings reveal an average price elasticity of 1.98, which means that a 10 percent increase in the price of metal leads to an approximate 20 percent increase in thefts.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] According to the National Insurance Crime Bureau, there were 1,298 reported cases of catalytic converter theft in 2018, which increased to 14,433 in 2020.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] In 2022, it was reported that the number of catalytic converter thefts in the United States sharply rose to 153,000 total thefts for the year.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] From 2019 to 2020, thieves in the United Kingdom were targeting older-model hybrid cars (such as Toyota's hybrids) which have more precious metals than newer vehicles—sometimes worth more than the value of the car—leading to scarcity and long delays in replacing them.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] In 2021 a trend emerged in the Democratic Republic of the Congo where catalytic converters were alleged to be stolen for use in illicit street drug production.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] The drug, a powder known as "bombé," was said to be a mixture of powdered pills/vitamins and pulverized honeycomb structures of catalytic converters.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] In 2023, however, a study of various samples of the drug concluded that its alleged origin from catalytic exhausts was found to be unsubstantiated.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Various jurisdictions now require on-board diagnostics to monitor the function and condition of the emissions-control system, including the catalytic converter.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Vehicles equipped with OBD-II diagnostic systems are designed to alert the driver to a misfire condition by means of illuminating the "check engine" light on the dashboard, or flashing it if the current misfire conditions are severe enough to potentially damage the catalytic converter.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] On-board diagnostic systems take several forms.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Temperature sensors are used for two purposes.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] The first is as a warning system, typically on two-way catalytic converters such as those used on LPG forklifts.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] The function of the sensor is to warn of catalytic converter temperature above the safe limit of 750 °C (1,380 °F).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Modern catalytic-converter designs are not as susceptible to temperature damage and can withstand sustained temperatures of 900 °C (1,650 °F).
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Temperature sensors are also used to monitor catalyst functioning: usually two sensors will be fitted, with one before the catalyst and one after to monitor the temperature rise over the catalytic-converter core.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] The oxygen sensor is the basis of the closed-loop control system on a spark-ignited rich-burn engine; however, it is also used for diagnostics.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] In vehicles with OBD II, a second oxygen sensor is fitted after the catalytic converter to monitor the O2 levels.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] The O2 levels are monitored to see the efficiency of the burn process.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] The on-board computer makes comparisons between the readings of the two sensors.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] The readings are taken by voltage measurements.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] If both sensors show the same output or the rear O2 is "switching", the computer recognizes that the catalytic converter either is not functioning or has been removed, and will operate a malfunction indicator lamp and affect engine performance.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Simple "oxygen sensor simulators" have been developed to circumvent this problem by simulating the change across the catalytic converter with plans and pre-assembled devices available on the Internet.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Although these are not legal for on-road use, they have been used with mixed results.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] Similar devices apply an offset to the sensor signals, allowing the engine to run a more fuel-economical lean burn that may, however, damage the engine or the catalytic converter.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] NO*x* sensors are extremely expensive and are in general used only when a compression-ignition engine is fitted with a selective catalytic-reduction (SCR) converter, or a NO*x* absorber in a feedback system.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] When fitted to an SCR system, there may be one or two sensors.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] When one sensor is fitted it will be pre-catalyst; when two are fitted, the second one will be post-catalyst.
[src:air-fuel-ratio/catalytic-converter] They are used for the same reasons and in the same manner as an oxygen sensor; the only difference is the substance being monitored.
